In other words, you scored 0.5 standard deviations above the class mean
on the research mid-term and 1.0 standard deviation below the class mean
on the statistics mid-term. Therefore, you could argue that you performed
better on the research exam, relative to the other students in the class.
When a z score is a whole number, we can return to Figure 3.6 to
calculate the percentile for the raw score. In the above example, the z
score for the statistics exam was 1.0. Looking at Figure 3.6, we can eas-
ily determine that 34.13% of the values fall between the raw score (84%)
and the mean (86%). To calculate the percentile, we simply subtract 34.13
from 50 to determine that 15.87% of the class scored less than 84% on
this test.
How do we calculate a percentile for a z score that is not a whole
number? To convert fractional z scores to percentiles, we must turn to a
table that displays the areas under the normal curve (go to the website
http://www.statsoft.com/textbook/distribution-tables/ for an example
standard normal z table). First ignoring the sign of your z score, nd the
rst digits of the z score in the left-hand column. Next, move across the
row to nd the second decimal. The value that appears in the table is the
area between your raw score and the mean. You then have to convert this
value to the percentile.
First, multiply the area from the table by 100 to give you the percent-
age of values that falls between your raw score and the mean. If your
Inferential Statistics 49
z score is positive (i.e., the raw score is greater than the mean), the score
on the table represents the percentage of values from the mean to the
right until you reach the raw score. Therefore, you add 50 to the percent-
age from the chart to account for the percentage of values that lie to the
left of the mean or center line. If your z score is negative (i.e., the raw
score is less than the mean), the table represents the percentage of values
from the mean to the left until you reach the raw score. Therefore, to cal-
culate the percentile (the percentage of values that falls below your raw
score), you subtract the percentage identi ed in the table from 50.
Returning to our prior example, how do we calculate the exact per-
centile for our raw score of 74 and a z score of 0.5? Looking at the standard
normal z table, look down the rst column until you get to 0.5. Go to the
right to the next column which represents the z score, 0.50. The value in
the table is .1915. Multiply this value by 100 to get 19.15. Because the z
score is positive, we add 50 to 19.15 to get a percentile of 69.15. Therefore,
we scored at the 15.87th percentile on our statistics mid-term and at the
69.15th percentile on the research mid-term, making another argument
that we performed better on the research test even though our raw score
was higher on the statistics test. This example highlights one way z scores
are used to determine percentile ranks when dealing with normal distri-
butions. In general, standard scores follow the same distributions as the
variables on which they are based, and can be used in a variety of more
advanced statistical techniques that are not covered in this text.
The Assumption of Normality in Statistical Estimation
In subsequent chapters, we describe procedures for statistical estimation
using multiple linear regression, Analysis of Variance and Covariance, and
path analysis. Each method is a parametric test that assumes a normal dis-
tribution of the dependent variable. We can determine the extent to which
a distribution is normal by plotting the observations on a histogram (dis-
cussed in Chapter 2) or calculating skewness and kurtosis statistics in
SPSS. In a normal distribution, skewness and kurtosis statistics equal 0.
The further these values are from 0, the more likely it is that the distribu-
tion is not normal (i.e., skewed and/or kurtotic). By convention, skew-
ness statistics with values absolute values greater than 1.96 deviate beyond
acceptable limits of normality. Kurtosis statistics with values absolute val-
ues greater than 3.29 deviate beyond acceptable limits of normality.
50 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
RESEARCH SAMPLING
If we only needed statistics to summarize the data we have collected and
to describe the distribution of the values of one or more variables within
our sample or population, we could use the information in the preced-
ing sections of this book to meet our needs. However, we often want to
discover if there is a relationship between variables or between different
samples. For example, we may want to know if a drug abuse prevention
program is more effective when we offered it to eighth grade students or
sixth grade students. Or is a self-esteem intervention delivered to middle
school youth more effective if given in a co-ed class or in classrooms
where boys and girls are separated? Or, does a persons age affect his or
her ability to learn new job skills at a job training center? This is where we
turn to inferential statistics.
There are really two steps involved in answering these questions.
The rst step is to determine whether there is a relationship between the
variables within the sample or samples we actually have studied. We will
return to this question later in the chapter, and we will cover statistical
techniques involved in answering this question in the remaining chapters
of this book. The second step is to assess a level of con dence that the
ndings based on our sample would hold true with other samples drawn
from the same population. This is an indicator of external validity of a
studythe extent to which results can be generalized to other samples.
For instance, if we discover that the self-esteem program we offered in
our middle school was more effective when we divided the girls and boys
than when we placed them in a group together, how con dent are we that
this would hold true for another group of middle school students in the
middle school, or to other middle school students arounds the state, or
the country? These are much larger questions, and relate to the next topic
we will discuss: research sampling.
Research sampling is the process of obtaining participants for our
research study. The sample may consist of people, couples, families, com-
munities, schools, states, organizations, or almost anything else research-
ers might be interested in studying. In elds other than social work, a
sample may consist of rats, cells, germs, or rocks. Researchers select a
sample, because it is generally impractical to study an entire population.
However, it is not impossible. If a historian wants to analyze the leader-
ship styles of the United States presidents, he may decide to include all of
Inferential Statistics 51
the presidents. However, if the same historian wants to analyze the lead-
ership styles of all of the men and women who have served in the United
States Congress, he would most likely select a sample. It is less expensive
and takes much less time to study one or more samples from a popula-
tion rather than the entire population.
How are the areas under the curves for a normal distribution related
to the question of how con dently we can generalize our ndings? We
stated earlier that inferential statistics make it possible for us to deter-
mine if ndings from our sample can be generalized to the larger popula-
tion. The accuracy of these generalizations depends on how closely our
sample represents the population. If the sample accurately represents
the population from which it is drawn, then generalizations made based
on the sample will be accurate as well, and the study is thought to have
strong external validity . The representativeness of the sample depends
primarily on whether the sample is randomly selected from the larger
population.
Random sampling refers to sampling techniques in which each ele-
ment in the population has a known and equal chance of being selected.
Random-sampling procedures are used to strengthen a studys external
validity, or the extent to which the results can be generalized to other
samples outside of the study. Nonrandom sampling refers to sampling
techniques in which each element in the population has an unknown
and usually unequal chance of being selected (for a more detailed discus-
sion of various random and nonrandom sampling techniques, see Krysik
& Finn, 2010; Rubin & Babbie, 2008; or Yegidis, Weinbach, & Myers,
2012).
Before we move on, it is useful to clarify the difference between ran-
dom sampling and random assignment. Random sampling involves
the process of selecting a sample of study participants from the larger
population. Random sampling is used to strengthen external validity, or
the extent to which the ndings from the sample can be generalized to
the larger population. On the other hand, random assignment occurs
after the studys sample has been selected, and involves assigning partici-
pants to experimental or control groups on the basis of chance. Random
assignment is used to strengthen a studys internal validity , or the extent
to which explanations for the studys ndings (i.e., effect) can be attrib-
uted to the experiment (i.e., cause), and alternative explanations for the
cause and effect relationship can be ruled out.
52 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
If our sample is selected from the population using a nonrandom
sampling method, there is likely to be a difference between our sample
and the population from which it was drawn. This difference, called
the sampling error, may be substantial. If the sample is selected using
a random-sampling method, the sampling error will likely be much
smaller. For example, suppose a university professor wanted to survey the
students in her university. If she surveyed only students in her social work
classes, the sample would probably differ substantially from the larger
university. If she surveyed students in every department on campus, but
selected only those students that were most convenient to survey, the
sample would more closely represent the university students, but would
still most likely differ from the population of all university students. If,
on the other hand, the professor got a list of all the universitys students
and randomly selected her sample from the list, the sample would more
closely represent the population of university students.
If random sampling is used, does it guarantee that the sample will
perfectly represent the population? Unfortunately, it does not. We can
assume that even a sample drawn randomly will differ in some aspects
from the population from which it was drawn. We may nd that a rela-
tionship between variables exists in the sample, when, in fact, the same
relationship does not exist in the population. On the contrary, a relation-
ship may not exist in the sample, while it does exist in the population. Or,
the relationship may exist in both the sample and the population or may
not exist in the sample or the population.
There are many reasons why a relationship found between variables
in a sample may not re ect the true relationship in the population. Three
common reasons why researchers misjudge relationships between vari-
ables are measurement error, sampling bias, and sampling error.
Measurement error. If we measure the variables of interest within
our sample incorrectly or in such a way as to introduce bias, then our
conclusions are likely to not hold true for the larger population. They may
not even hold true for our sample! There are two basic types of measure-
ment error: systematic-measurement error and random-measurement
error. Systematic-measurement error represents discrepancies between
measured and actual (true) values of a variable, where the values of the
measured variable are more likely to be higher or lower than the actual
values of the variable. Systematic-measurement errors are caused by aws
in the measurement process, and they lead to over- or underestimates of
Inferential Statistics 53
the actual values of a variable. This type of error is also known as bias
in measurement. For example, suppose the researcher wishes to compare
outcomes of an ADHD intervention with a group of second grade chil-
dren to the same intervention with a group of fourth grade children. She
creates a behavioral observation protocol to count the number of times
the children disrupt the class. The researcher decides to observe each class
immediately after their recess periods in order to make the observation
periods as similar as possible. However, the second grade children have
their recess at 9 am while the fourth grade children have their recess at 2
pm . The researcher concludes that the second grade children responded
much better to the intervention. In reality, the ADHD medications may
simply be wearing off for many of the fourth grade children by 2 pm
making them appear to react much more poorly to the intervention.
Random-measurement error is just that: random. It does not follow
a pattern. It represents the discrepancies between measured and actual
(true) values of a variable, where the values of the measured variable are
equally likely to be higher or lower than the actual values because they are
caused by chance uctuations in measurement. Random-measurement
errors are caused by aws in the measurement process and they tend to
cancel each other out and average to zero; however, they increase the vari-
ability of measured values. Random-measurement error is also known
as unsystematic measurement error. Building on our previous exam-
ple, suppose the researcher realizes her mistake and repeats the ADHD
intervention study with two classes that both have recess in the morn-
ing, and the measurements are taken immediately following the recess
periods. The school counselor is recruited to gather the measurements.
Unfortunately, during some of the observation sessions, the school coun-
selor is very alert and attentive, noting each and every disruption among
the students. Other times she is distracted by other tasks, sometimes
even bringing other work into the observation room with her. On those
days, only a portion of the class disruptions are noted on the observa-
tion sheets. This creates random-measurement error, because there is no
de nite pattern of error, but depends solely on the circumstances of the
observer. Clearly, either type of measurement error can lead to invalid
conclusions regarding the relationships between variables in the study.
Sampling bias. Sampling bias is the intended or unintended system-
atic distortion of a sample. Sampling bias results in a lack of represen-
tativeness of the sample to the population from which it is drawn. The
54 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
most effective way to avoid sampling bias is to use a random-sampling
technique to select your research sample. Random assignment is also
used in experimental research designs to reduce sampling bias. Random
assignment means that the elements in our sample are randomly assigned
to the different groups within the research study, for example, the experi-
mental and the control groups. As mentioned previously, random assign-
ment is used in order to strengthen a studys internal validity. Finally,
the size of our sample affects the amount of sampling bias present in a
research study. The larger the sample size, the more closely it will repre-
sent the population on all known variables, as well as variables that have
not even been identi ed that may affect the outcome.
Sampling error. Large sample sizes, random sampling, and ran-
dom assignment are used to reduce the effects of sampling bias as much
as possible. But, regardless of the research design and the researchers
efforts to select a completely unbiased and representative sample, there
will still be some sampling error. Suppose we have a population of 100
students and we randomly select 30 of the students. The chance that
the mean age of the sample will be exactly equal to the mean age of the
population is very small. If we draw a sample of 60 students, we might
expect the mean age of the sample to be closer to the population mean,
but it will probably still not be exactly the same. Sampling error is the
tendency for any sample to differ from the population from which it
was drawn. It represents the discrepancy between values in a population
and values in a sample (i.e., discrepancy between parameters and sta-
tistics). The smaller the sample, the larger the expected sampling error.
Therefore, any time a relationship is found between two variables within
a sample, there is always a chance that this relationship is just a uke
and does not exist in the population. Alternately, if a relationship is not
found between variables in a sample, the relationship may in fact exist
in the population.
There are two basic methods for determining if a relationship found
in a research sample is likely to be the result of sampling error. These are
replication and conducting inferential statistical tests. Replication is the
process of repeating a research study two or more times using the same
population but different samples to see if the same conclusions are found.
Clearly, if the same relationship is found using three different random
samples, the chance that the relationship can be explained by sampling
error is much less than if we used only one sample.
Inferential Statistics 55
Inferential statistical methods allow us to estimate the probability
that an observed relationship between two variables within our sample
is actually caused by sampling error rather than an actual relationship.
If we conclude that the relationship between variables in our sample is a
real one and our sample is suf ciently representative of the population
of interest, then we can make the inference that the same relationship
exists within the population. Inferential statistical techniques, therefore,
provide a basis for generalizing our ndings to the larger population.
The basic logic behind inferential statistics is the focus of the remainder
of this chapter.
SAMPLING DISTRIBUTION OF MEANS
The next step in understanding the underlying logic of inferential statis-
tics is to understand the sampling distribution of means . Suppose we
select a random sample of 30 social workers and calculate their mean
income to be $45,000 a year. Now suppose we take four more random
samples of 30 social workers each and calculate the mean incomes for
each group. Would you expect the mean incomes for these groups to be
the same as the rst group? Probably not. Suppose the mean incomes for
these groups are $38,000, $36,500, $49,000, and $50,500. If we continue
to select random groups of 30 social workers each, we will get a variety
of mean incomes for these groups. If we look at the distribution of these
sample means, you may have guessed that they will begin to follow a nor-
mal curve. If we draw a large enough number of samples, a theoretically
in nite number of samples, the distribution of these sample means will
follow a normal curve and the mean of the sample means will be a close
estimate of the true population mean.
Another useful fact is that regardless of whether or not the popula-
tion is normally distributed and whether or not our sample observations
are normally distributed, the means of the samples will approximate
a normal distribution. The larger the number of samples, the more
closely the distribution of the sample means will approximate a normal
distribution.
In addition to having a mean that closely approximates the popula-
tion mean, the sampling distribution of means also has a standard devia-
tion. The standard deviation of the sample means is smaller than the
56 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
standard deviation of the population. In other words, the means of our
samples will not differ from each other as much as the actual raw val-
ues in our population. The standard deviation of the sample means is
referred to as the standard error of the mean to distinguish it from the
sample and population standard deviations.
The standard error of the mean is basically related to two factors:
the size of our sample and the standard deviation of our population.
Unfortunately, we generally do not know the population standard devia-
tion. Luckily, if we have a sample size of at least 30 elements, the standard
deviation of the sample is a good estimate of the population standard
deviation. Therefore, we can calculate the standard error of the mean
with only the sample size and sample standard deviation. Surprisingly,
the size of the sample is much more signi cant than the proportion of
the population covered by the sample. A sample size of 2,000 provides
an accurate estimation of a population whether the population contains
4,000 elements or 4,000,000 elements.
The standard error of the mean will be smaller than the sample stan-
dard deviation. How much smaller depends on the size of our sample.
The formula for calculating the standard error of the mean (SE) looks
like this:

Con dence Interval
When using inferential statistics, we do not actually create a distribution
of sample means. The sampling distribution of means is more a theoreti-
cal concept than an actual practice. We base our inferences on only one
sample with one sample mean and one sample standard deviation. The
mean of our sample is viewed as one value in the normal distribution
of sample means. We can therefore use the information we have already
discovered about normal distributions, mainly the information displayed
earlier in Figure 3.6, to infer certain facts about our sample and the popu-
lation. For example, because we know that our sampling distribution of
means is normal, we can assume that our sample mean will fall within
one SE on either side of the true population mean 68.26% of the time.
Inferential Statistics 57
Likewise, we know that our sample mean will fall within three SEs of the
true population mean 99.74% of the time.
Looking at it another way, we also nd that the true population mean
will fall within the range of plus or minus one SE from our sample mean
68.26% of the time. For example, suppose we have test scores for 30 cli-
ents, with a sample mean of 60 and a sample standard deviation of 10.
The SE would be calculated as follows:

There is a 68.26% probability that the true population mean is within
plus or minus one standard error from the sample mean. Therefore,
there is a 68.26% chance that the true population mean is between 58.18
(60 1.82) and 61.82 (60 + 1.82). This range is called the 68% con -
dence interval. A con dence interval (CI) is a range of values around a
given statistic (e.g., the mean) that are believed to contain with a certain
probability (e.g., 95%) the true value of that statistic (i.e., the population
parameter) (Field, 2009, p. 783). You can also calculate the 95% con -
dence interval by adding and subtracting two standard errors from the
sample mean: 56.36 (60 3.64) and 63.64 (60 + 3.64). A 95% con dence
interval indicates that there is a 95% probability that any given 95% con-
dence interval contains that population parameter. Finally the 99.74%
con dence interval would be from 54.54 (60 5.46) and 65.46 (60 +
5.46), indicating that we can be 99.74% con dent that the true popula-
tion mean falls within this interval. Note that this formula to calculate
con dence intervals applies only to normal-shaped distributions (Field,
2009).
Con dence intervals are set a priori , usually at either 95% or 99%.
They can be displayed in an error bar graph, which shows the range of val-
ues (i.e., interval) around the statistic of interest (e.g., the sample mean).
The error bar resembles the letter I, with a point value of a sample sta-
tistic plotted somewhere along the I. On a graph, the error bar starts at
the lower CI value, and ends at the upper value. Thus, we can actually see
how precise the sample statistic is in terms of re ecting the population
parameter. The longer the error bar, the less precise our sample statistic
is. Field (2009) provides instructions on how to plot con dence intervals
on an error bar graph using SPSS.
58 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
HYPOTHESIS TESTING
In the preceding section, we looked at how a theoretical sampling dis-
tribution can help us estimate the true population mean. Similar logic
can help us determine the probability that an apparent relationship
between two variables may be explained by sampling error. This actu-
ally involves looking at the values of two variables and determining the
probability that these two sets of values came from the same popula-
tion. For example, suppose a school social worker wanted to determine
if there was a difference in absenteeism between male and female high
school students. Inferential statistics could compare the absentee rates
of the male students and female students to determine the chances that
the males and females were drawn from the same population. If there is
a high probability that the absentee rates for male and female students
are drawn from the same population, then the school social worker
would conclude that there is not a signi cant difference between male
and female absenteeism. On the other hand, if there is a high prob-
ability that the two sets of rates could not be drawn from the same
population, then the school social worker could conclude that there
is a signi cant difference between male and female absenteeism. This
process forms the basis for null hypothesis signi cance testing, and of
inferential statistics.
Comparing Two Samples
Previously we looked at how the theoretical sampling distribution of
means can be used to estimate the true population mean. Another dis-
tribution is used to estimate whether two samples have been drawn from
the same or different populations. Not surprisingly, this distribution is
the sampling distribution of the differences between means . To create
this theoretical distribution, let us continue with the previous example.
We would draw multiple samples of, say, 30 male high school students
and 30 female high school students. For each pair of samples, we calculate
the mean absentee rate for the males and the mean absentee rate for the
females. Even if there is no difference between the male and female absen-
tee rates, we would not expect the means of these groups to be exactly the
same in every case. In some cases, the difference would be positive (male
sample mean is larger than female sample mean) and in some cases, the
Inferential Statistics 59
difference would be negative (male sample mean is smaller than female
sample mean). Suppose we draw an in nite number of pairs of samples
(theoretically of course) and calculate the difference between the means.
We could then create a distribution from these differences.
Like the sampling distribution of means, the sampling distribution
of the differences between the means would also approximate a normal
distribution. If the two samples are from the same population, the mean
of the distribution would be 0. In other words, if the samples are from
the same population, then the differences between the sample means
would center at 0, with progressively fewer of the sample pairs having
large positive differences (male sample mean is much higher than the
female sample mean) or large negative differences (male sample mean
is much lower than the female sample mean). While the mean of this
distribution is 0, the variability or standard deviation of this sampling
distribution would depend on the standard deviation of the population.
While the standard deviation of the sampling distribution of the sample
means is called the standard error of the mean, the standard deviation of
the sampling distribution of the differences between the means is called
the standard error of the differences between means (SE-Diff). Because
the standard deviation of the population is unknown, we again must esti-
mate the SE-Diff. This is done by combining the standard error of the
means (SE) for both of our samples (males and females). The formula for
calculating the SE-Diff is as follows:

The null hypothesis for this example would read:
There is no difference between male and female absentee rates.
A two-tailed research hypothesis would read:
There is a difference between male and female absentee rates.
A one-tailed research hypothesis could be stated in two different direc-
tions depending on the school social workers hypothesis:
The male absentee rate is higher than the female absentee rate.
or:
The female absentee rate is higher than the male absentee rate.
If the null hypothesis is true (the two samples are not signi cantly
different), then the sampling distribution of the differences between the
means of pairs of samples would be approximately normal, have a mean
of 0, and a standard deviation (or SE-Diff) of about 0.53. Therefore, if
there is no difference between these two samples (males and females), the
sample means would still differ by up to 0.53 in either direction 68.26%
of the time (plus or minus one standard deviation from the mean). The
sample means would differ by 1.06 (plus or minus two standard devia-
tions from the mean) 95.44% of the time, and by 1.59 (plus or minus
three standard deviations from the mean) 99.74% of the time. In other
words, if our two samples do not differ, the two sample means would dif-
fer by more than 1.59 only 0.26% of the time.
Rejection Level
The researcher, or school social worker in this example, would decide
how much difference between samples would be enough difference to
Inferential Statistics 61
be considered signi cant before the data are collected. This is referred to
as the rejection level or signi cance level, denoted by D (Greek alpha).
Suppose the social worker chose a .05 D or rejection level. The rejection
level indicates the probability of nding a relationship between variables
in the sample as strong as the one observed when, in fact, there is not a
real relationship between the variables in the population. In other words,
the rejection level is the chance we are willing to accept of rejecting the
null hypothesis, when, in fact, the null hypothesis is true. If we set our
rejection level at .05, this means the null hypothesis will be rejected if
there is less than a 5% chance that the relationship between the two vari-
ables can be explained by sampling error.
In our example, the difference between the two sample means is 4.5%
(9.5% 5%). Because the SE-Diff of our sampling distribution is .53,
this means that the difference between the means of our two samples is
approximately 8 standard deviations from the mean (4.5/.53 = 8.5).
Looking back at Figure 3.6, we can see that a difference this large between
means of two samples drawn from the same population could only be
explained by sampling error a negligible amount of the time. Because the
5% rejection region for a one-tailed hypothesis starts at 1.645 standard
deviations (see Figure 3.9), this nding is well within the rejection region.
Therefore, if the rejection level is set at .05 or 5%, the social worker would
reject the null hypothesis and conclude, based on this information, that
there is a relationship between gender and absenteeism in the high
school.
One-tailed versus two-tailed hypotheses. We discussed earlier the
difference between a one-tailed or directional hypothesis and a two-
tailed or nondirectional hypothesis. How does this affect the school social
workers decision as to whether gender and absentee rates differ? Let us

5%
Figure 3.9 Example of a One-Tailed Rejection Region.
62 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
look at this example using two different hypotheses. First, suppose the
school social worker stated her research hypothesis that:
There is a difference between male and female absentee rates.
This is a two-tailed or nondirectional hypothesis. Looking at Figure 3.10,
you will see that there is a rejection region that lies at both the extreme
right and extreme left ends of the graph. Because the rejection region
has been set at 5%, this percentage must be split between the right end
and the left end of the distribution. There is a 2.5% rejection region rep-
resented at the far left end of the graph, and a 2.5% rejection region at
the far right of the graph. The rejection region on the right side starts at
1.96 standard deviations and the rejection region on the left side starts
at 1.96 standard deviations. In our example, the male sample mean was
signi cantly larger than the female sample mean so our difference lay at
the far right end of the graph in the rejection region. If the female sample
mean had been signi cantly larger than the male sample mean, the dif-
ference would have fallen in the rejection region at the far left end of the
graph, and the null hypothesis would have still been rejected.
Signi cance Testing
The statistical tests described throughout the rest of this book identify
the probability ( p value) that a relationship found between two variables
may have been produced by sampling error. The p value indicates the
probability of nding a relationship between variables in the sample as
strong as the one observed when, in fact, there is not a real relationship
between the variables in the population. The p value ranges from 0.00
01.961.96
2.5% 2.5%
Figure 3.10 Example of a Two-Tailed Rejection Region.
Inferential Statistics 63
to 1.00. A p value of 0.00 indicates that, assuming the null hypothesis is
true, there would be no chance that the relationship observed could be
explained by sampling error. A p value of 1.00 indicates that the relation-
ship could de nitely be explained by sampling error. You would likely
never see a p value at either extreme, but theoretically it is possible. The
closer the p value is to 1.00, the more likely sampling error can explain
the relationship. Alternately, the closer the p value is to 0.00, the less likely
the relationship can be explained by sampling error, and the more likely
there is a true relationship between the variables.
If the p value is small enough, the researcher will reject the null
hypothesis that there is no relationship between variables and support the
research hypothesis that there is a relationship between the variables. The
researcher must decide what is small enough. Many researchers agree that
if we are 95% sure that the relationship is not caused by sampling error, it
is reasonable to conclude that a relationship between the variables prob-
ably exists. Remember, we can never completely rule out the chance that
sampling error has caused the relationship. A p value less than or equal
to 0.05 indicates that we are at least 95% certain the relationship is a real
one. This is referred to as a .05 rejection level. When researchers want to
be more con dent that sampling error cannot explain the relationship,
they may select a rejection level of .01. They can then be 99% certain that
the relationship actually exists in the population.
In some software packages, such as SPSS, the calculated p value corre-
sponds only to a nondirectional or two-tailed hypothesis. If the research
hypothesis is directional or one-tailed, rst the researcher must check
to see if the difference is in the direction that he or she predicted. If it is,
then the p value given is simply divided by two to indicate the chance that
the relationship can be explained by sampling error. If the p value is less
than the rejection level selected, the researcher rejects the null hypothesis
and concludes that the relationship predicted in the research hypothesis
is statistically signi cant.
Cummings (2012) provides a caution with regard to interpreting
the p value in null hypothesis signi cance testing. He suggests that the
correct interpretation of the p value is the probability of getting our
observed result, or a more extreme result, if the null hypothesis were true
(p. 27). Note that p is interpreted based on the assumption that the null
hypothesis is true (i.e., there is no difference or relationship between the
variables). Note also that p does not provide the probability that the null
64 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
is true (p. 27). According to Cummings, another misuse of p is to inter-
pret its value on what he refers to as a sliding scale of degrees of statisti-
cal signi cance (p. 29), such that the smaller the p value the stronger
the relationship or effect. The p value simply tells us whether there is a
relationship between two variables; it does not indicate the strength of
the relationship. The strength of a relationship between two variables is
provided by an effect size measure, which is de ned later in this chapter
and then described in subsequent chapters as it relates to interpreting the
ndings of the different statistical tests.
Type I and Type II Errors
If the p value is within the rejection level (i.e., p .05), does that mean
there is de nitely a relationship between the variables? No, it does not.
It means that we can be at least 95% con dent that there is a relation-
ship. We may be incorrect. For example, if the p value is .03, there is still
a 3% chance that we will reject the null hypothesis and conclude that
the relationship between the variables is a real one when in fact there
is not a real relationship between the variables. This is called a Ty pe I
error . When the p value is greater than our selected rejection level (i.e.,
p > .05), we fail to reject the null hypothesis and conclude that there
is not a real relationship between the variables. However, if the p value
is .10, then there is a 10% chance that we will fail to reject the null
hypothesis and conclude that there is not a real relationship between
the variables when in fact there is. This is called a Type II error . These
errors are not only caused by sampling error. They can be caused by
measurement bias, design aws, or using the wrong statistical test,
among others things.
The researcher does have some control over the possibility of commit-
ting these errors. As we noted earlier, the researcher selects the rejection
level. When we set the rejection region at .05, it means that we are willing
to tolerate making a Type I error up to 5% of the time. We can reduce our
rejection level to .01 to reduce our acceptance of making a Type I error.
However, when we do this, we increase the chance that a Type II error
will be committed. It is up to the researcher to decide whether commit-
ting a Type I error (concluding that there is a relationship when there is
not) or a Type II error (concluding that there is not a relationship when
there is) would be more detrimental to the research or dangerous to the
Inferential Statistics 65
participants. Based on this, he or she can identify the rejection level to be
used. See Table 3.1 for a summary of Type I and Type II errors.
One way we can simultaneously reduce our chances of committing a
Type I or Type II error is to increase our sample size. The larger our sam-
ple, the closer our sample will represent the larger population. This means
there will be less sampling error. With less sampling error, we increase the
probability that a relationship found in our sample can allow us to accu-
rately predict that the same relationship will be found in the population.
Statistical Power Analysis and Effect Size
More emphasis has been placed in the literature recently on avoiding Type
II errors. Researchers have realized that missing relationships between
variables that may in fact be signi cant ones may cause us to reject help-
ful treatment strategies or ignore variables that might help us predict cli-
ent problems. The power of a statistical test refers to the chance that the
test will avoid making a Type II error. Statistical power is the probability
that the researcher will reject the null hypothesis when, in fact, it is false.
In other words, the researcher will conclude, based on the p value, that
there is a relationship between variables when there actually is a relation-
ship. Power can be increased by increasing the rejection level, but this will
also increase the chance of making a Type I error. Increasing the sample
size is generally considered the easiest way to boost the statistical power
of a test. A power analysis should be conducted during the design stage of
a research study to determine the minimum sample size needed to keep
the probability of committing a Type II error to an acceptable level.
One condition that relates to the power of the statistical analysis of
a sample of data is the actual strength of the relationship that exists in
the population. Of course, this is not something the researcher has any
control over. The strength of this relationship, however, can be estimated.
Table 3.1 Hypothesis Decision Table

66 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
This estimation is called the effect size . While the p value tells us whether
the IV has an effect on the DV, the effect-size (ES) estimates the amount
of in uence the IV has on the DV. It is an indicator of the strength
(i.e., magnitude) and (typically) direction of relationship between the
variables. It is clearly informative, beyond information provided by
the p value. Thus, there has been increasing interest in and emphasis
on effect-size measures. In fact, the APA Manual (2010) recommends
reporting effect sizes in inferential statistical testing. It is conventional to
report the con dence interval (CI) usually at either 95% or 99%, along
with an effect-size measure. Make sure to distinguish between the true
ES (i.e., the unknown population parameter) and the observed ES from
the sample. To learn more about effect sizes, see Cumming (2012) or
Grissom and Kim (2012).
The following is the formula to estimate the effect size in a research
study that compares outcomes of an experimental group to a control
group to evaluate the effectiveness of an intervention:

For example, suppose we had 40 clients randomly assigned to an
experimental group that received behavioral treatment plus medication
to treat obsessivecompulsive disorder (OCD). Another group of 40 cli-

disorder. The mean posttest score on the OCD symptom checklist (higher
scores represent more severe OCD symptoms) for the experimental group
was 40, and the mean score for the control group was 50, with a standard
deviation of 5. Suppose an inferential statistical test was performed and it
was found that the difference between these mean scores was statistically
signi cant using a .05 rejection level (i.e., p < .05).
This tells us that the difference between the groups is large enough
that it is unlikely to be the cause of sampling error. However, it does not
tell us how much effect the treatment had on the OCD symptoms. To

Therefore, the mean for the experimental group was two standard devia-

was lower than 97.72% of the scores of the people in the control group.
Another strength of effect size is that, much like the similar z score, effect
sizes from different studies can be calculated and compared even when
different outcome measures and research designs are used.
Statistically Signi cant versus Meaningful Relationships
When the researcher nds a statistically signi cant relationship between
two variables, it means that it is unlikely that the relationship could have
been caused by sampling error. In other words, the relationship is likely
a real one. However, this does not necessarily mean it is a meaningful or
even an interesting relationship. For example, suppose 800 high school
seniors were randomly assigned to complete an SAT preparation work-
shop before taking the SAT test. Another 600 students were randomly
assigned to simply prepare on their own using an SAT preparation man-
ual. After completing their preparation and taking the SAT, the mean SAT
score for the rst group was 1240 and the mean score for the second
group was 1220. Based on the large sample size, this 20-point difference
may be statistically signi cant. But if the workshop costs the school sys-
tem $200 per student and the preparation manual costs $20, would a
difference of 20 points be considered a meaningful enough difference to
warrant the nancial expenditure? Maybe not. Therefore, the researcher
must also consider the practical signi cance of the ndings.
In this chapter, we have presented a foundation for understanding
how and why inferential statistics can be used to determine if there is
a relationship between the variables of interest in a research study. In
the following chapters, we will present the inferential statistical methods
most commonly used in social work research.

4
Bivariate Statistical
Methods
INTRODUCTION
In the previous chapter, we looked at the concept of statistical inference
and how it is used to test research hypotheses. The research hypothesis
is a predictive statement regarding the relationship between two or more
variables. In this chapter, we will review bivariate statistical methods used
to determine the probability that a relationship found between two vari-
ables is based on sampling error. There are many bivariate methods, more
than we can cover in this book. We will focus on the methods most com-
monly used in social work research, including the chi-square test, one-
sample t -test, dependent-samples t -test, independent-samples t -test, and
linear correlation. It is important to understand how researchers select
the appropriate statistical test to use in a given research study. Weinbach
and Grinnell (2010) point out the ve considerations that most directly
in uence this choice: 1) the sampling method used; 2) the distribution
of the variables within the population; 3) the level of measurement of
the independent and dependent variables; 4) the amount of statistical
power that is desirable; and 5) the robustness of the tests being consid-
ered (p. 126).
70 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
PARAMETRIC AND NONPARAMETRIC TESTS
There are two basic types of statistical tests: parametric and nonpara-
metric . The key difference between parametric and nonparametric tests
is that, for the most part, nonparametric tests do not require assump-
tions about the population (i.e., parametric assumptions). Parametric
tests have greater power (e.g., the ability to detect small but nonrandom
differences) than their nonparametric alternatives. In other words, they
are more likely to detect a relationship between two variables when there
is, in fact, a relationship. In order to use a parametric test, four assump-
tions must be met:
At least one variable (usually the DV) is measured at the interval
or ratio level.
The shape of the distribution of the DV should approach the
shape of a normal curve (i.e., unimodal, not skewed, and not
kurtotic).
The basis of hypothesis testing is that the data are normally distrib-
uted. Thus, nonnormal distributions affect our ability to test hypotheses
accurately. Generally nonnormal distributions occur when there are
extreme observations (i.e., outliers or in uential cases) in the data set.
These extreme observations can lead to inaccurate results of our analyses.
Violations of the normality assumption can be detected graphically by
creating a histogram, frequency distribution, or boxplot of the observa-
tions, and then examining its symmetry. The companion website pro-
vides step-by-step instructions for assessing violations of the normality
assumption with a histogram. Skewness and kurtosis statistics also pro-
vide information about the normality of a distribution. In a normal dis-
tribution, these values are 0. Thus, the further away they are from 0, the
more likely the distribution deviates from normality.
If two samples drawn from two different populations are being
compared, the variances of these different populations should be
at least approximately equal.
This assumption is referred to as homogeneity of variance or homo-
scedasticity. A violation of this assumption (i.e., unequal variances) is
Bivariate Statistical Methods 71
referred to as heteroscedasticity . When this assumption is violated in
multiple regression analysis, the estimated regression coef cients are not
necessarily affected. However, violations may result in in ated standard
errors, and thus an increased likelihood of making a Type II error (fail-
ing to reject a false null hypothesis and discarding an IV that is actually
signi cant).
The Levene test for homogeneity of variance can be used to evalu-
ate whether the homogeneity of variance assumption has been violated.
If the test statistic is nonsigni cant, then we retain the null hypothesis
that the difference between the variance equals 0, and the assumption has
been met. Note that the Levene test is affected by sample size such that, in
large samples, it can be signi cant even when variances are not different.
In this case, we recommend calculating the variance ratio. SPSS offers the
Hartleys F
MAX
procedure.
What can be done to correct for violations of this assumption? Minor
violations have a negligible impact on the results. To address serious vio-
lations, however, one can consider variance-stabilizing transformations,
such as taking the log or square root of Y (Lomax, 1992). Another option
is to use a different method of estimation that does not require homoge-
neity of variance, such as the weighted least-square method.
The observations are independent of one another.
This assumption means that the scores or observations of the DV
should not be correlated with one another. As an example, studies that
investigate educational questions among children across different class-
rooms may be at risk of violating this assumption because children in
one classroom are likely to have similar experiences with one another
(and thus have scores that are correlated with one another), relative to
children in other classrooms. This assumption is also more likely to be
violated in longitudinal panel studies, when multiple observations are
made on the same individuals over time. Violations of this assumption
require the use of different methods of analysis (e.g., hierarchical linear
modeling). Note that this assumption does not apply to statistical tests
(e.g., dependent-samples t -test, repeated measures ANOVA) associated
with research designs (e.g., experimental designs, panel studies) that
are based on data collected at more than one time point from the same
sample.
72 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
Some parametric tests have additional assumptions, and we may
be able to use some parametric tests even when one or more of these
assumptions are not met. However, before using any parametric test, it is
a good practice to ensure that the data being examined meet the speci c
assumptions of that test.
If the assumptions for parametric tests are not satisfactorily met,
then nonparametric tests may be used. Nonparametric tests have fewer
assumptions regarding data characteristics. For example, they can be
used with variables measured at the nominal or ordinal level, and the
dependent variable does not have to be normally distributed. There are
also nonparametric tests that can be used in studies with very small sam-
ple sizes.
Selection of the statistical test or tests to use requires that the researcher
consider the purpose of the research study, as well as the characteristics
of the data being analyzed. Factors to be considered include sampling
methods used, sample size, the level of measurement of each variable,
distribution of the variables, and possible confounding variables. You
must also consider the importance of avoiding Type I and Type II errors
for your speci c research question. All of these issues help determine the
most appropriate statistical test to use for a given research study.
GRAPHICAL REPRESENTATION
Cross-Tabulation Tables
The most common method for graphically displaying the relationship
between two nominal- or ordinal-level variables is the cross-tabulation
table . In a cross-tabulation table, the categories of one variable are dis-
played as rows in the table, and the categories of the second variable are
displayed as columns. If one of the variables is considered the IV and the
other is the DV, then generally the categories of the DV are displayed in
the columns. However, many researchers present categories of the DV in
the rows and categories of the IV in the columns, so it is important to
double check this. Both frequencies and percentages are often included,
as well as row totals and column totals.
Look at the cross-tabulation table shown in Table 4.1. What types of
questions can we answer about the relationship between the two vari-
ables college class and GPA? For instance, one might wonder whether
Bivariate Statistical Methods 73
GPAs increase or decrease as students move to the upper level classes.
There is a lot of information provided in a cross-tabulation table. Lets
examine the rows and columns. What do the row totals (the last column
on the right) and the column totals (the last row of gures) tell you? The
percentages in this table are called row percentages. In other words, 11%
of all freshmen (the top row of gures) have a GPA under 1.0. If you add
all of the percentages across the top row (excluding the cell showing the
total number of freshmen), they will add up to 100%. You can also use
column percentages if they more closely meet your needs. Sometimes,
you will nd both row and column percentages in a cross-tabulation
table. In these cases, there will be two percentages displayed in each cell
of the table, one indicating the percentage of the row total and the other
indicating the percentage of the column total.
We focus on bivariate statistical methods in this chapter, but we want
to mention that cross-tabulation tables can also be used to display the
relationship between more than two variables. Suppose we were inter-
ested in the pass/fail rates of our MSW students on a licensure test. We
are interested in comparing our full-time students versus our part-time
evening students, as well as those that entered as advanced standing
versus those who did not. Look at Table 4.2 for an example of how a
cross-tabulation table would display these data. Note in this table, we have
chosen to display percentages by column rather than by row, because we
are interested in the percentage of each group of students who passed or
failed the test. By looking at these data, would you think that these four
groups of students differed signi cantly on pass/fail rates? Probably not.
Later in this chapter we will look at speci c bivariate statistical methods
that are used to determine whether differences such as these are statisti-
cally signi cant.

Scattergram
The scattergram is another method for displaying the relationship
between two variables. Unlike the cross-tabulation table, the scattergram
displays every value of one variable on the x -axis along with every cor-
responding value of the second variable along the y -axis. Once the data
are plotted, the pattern of the points can suggest a possible relationship
between the two variables. Scattergrams are often used to check whether
parametric-test assumptions have been met.
Suppose we are interested in the relationship between depression level
and severity of eating disordered behaviors. Generally, you plot the IV
(or predictor variable) along the x -axis and the DV (or outcome variable)
along the y -axis. If we are hypothesizing that a clients eating disordered
behaviors affect or can predict (independent or predictor variable) their
depression level (dependent or outcome variable), then a scattergram
showing the relationship between these two variables would probably
plot the eating disordered behaviors on the x -axis and the depression
level on the y -axis.
In the scattergram displayed in Figure 4.1, the data indicate the higher
the severity of eating disordered behavior, the higher the depression level,
suggesting a positive correlation between these two variables. Figure 4.2
indicates the opposite, that the higher the severity of eating disordered
behavior, the lower the depression level. This would suggest a negative
correlation between the two variables. Finally, Figure 4.3 shows a scatter-
gram that suggests little or no relationship between the two variables. We
will look later in the chapter at a statistical test that can be used to deter-
mine whether correlations such as the ones shown in these scattergrams
are statistically signi cant.

CHI-SQUARE TEST OF ASSOCIATION
The chi-square (
2
) test measures the association between two variables
measured at the nominal or ordinal level. In other words, this test is used
with categorical variables only. The chi-square test can be used to test
whether there is a relationship between certain nominal level variables
and intervention success, and is used extensively in social work research.
For example, our IV might be gender (male/female), or group (inter-
vention/control), or type of treatment (cognitive-behavioral/behavioral
only/medications), or education level of therapist (bachelors/masters/
doctorate), and so forth. The DV, representing treatment success, could
be high school graduation (graduated/did not graduate), program com-
pletion (completed/did not complete), drug use (used/did not use), etc.
The chi-square test tells us if certain value categories of the IV tend to
cluster around certain value categories of the DV.
Suppose you want to evaluate a new retention program for high
school students who have been deemed at-risk for dropping out of
high school before graduation. At-risk students are randomly placed in
either the new retention program or they are placed in a control group
where they receive the traditional school counseling encouraging them
to remain in school. In this example, the IV is the group in which the
student is placed (retention program versus control group), and the DV
is high school graduation (graduated/did not graduate). The research
hypothesis for this study could be stated:
The students participating in the new retention program are more likely to
graduate high school than those students who receive traditional counseling
at the school.
Our corresponding null hypothesis would read:
There is no relationship between participation in the retention program
(versus traditional school counseling) and high school graduation.
The chi-square test would determine if students attending the new
retention program were more likely to graduate than the control students.
As you will see throughout this chapter and the ones that follow, each of
the statistical tests that we describe offer the value of the test statistic, as
Bivariate Statistical Methods 77
well as a p value. As you will remember from the previous chapter, the p
value indicates the chance that the relationship between the variables can
be explained by sampling error. If we nd that 84% of the students in the
retention group graduate, while only 64% of the control students gradu-
ate, we might conclude that the program was successful. But, depending
on our sample size, a difference of 20% might not be statistically signi -
cant. In other words, sampling error may be able to account for this dif-
ference. For example, say we had 30 students in the retention group and
30 students in the control group, then 25 (85%) from the retention group
and 19 (64%) from the control group subsequently graduated. For our
purposes, this may seem successful, but statistically the chance of this dif-
ference occurring because of sampling error (differences between the two
groups that are unaccounted for) may be relatively high, say .20. That is,
statistically there is a 20% chance that this difference could be explained
by sampling error. Suppose instead there are 300 students in each group,
where 252 of 300 students (85%) in the retention group graduated and
192 of 300 students (64%) in the control group graduated. Even though
the percentages of graduates in each group remain the same, this dif-
ference would almost certainly be statistically signi cant based on the
larger sample sizes in the two groups. In other words, as the sample size
increases, the sampling error decreases. Therefore, a smaller difference
between the two groups will be statistically signi cant.
Observed and Expected Frequencies
Several steps are involved in calculating a chi-square statistic. The rst
step is to create a cross-tabulation table of the data. Table 4.3 shows
the frequencies and percentages of the students by group. These are
the actual or observed frequencies . At this point, you must determine
if the frequency in each cell of the table is large enough to meet the
requirements of the chi-square test. The general rule of thumb is that
Table 4.3 High School Graduation by Group

Retention Group 48 (84%) 9 (16%) 57
Control Group 32 (64%) 18 (36%) 50
Total 80 27 107

there must be 5 or more in each cell of a chi-square test in which both
variables have two categories (2 2 table) and 5 or more in 80% of the
cells in larger tables. There can be no cells with a frequency of 0. Note
we included the row percentages in our cross-tabulation table because
we are interested in the percentage of students in the retention group
that graduated, rather than the percentage of graduates who were in the
retention group. Each time you create a cross-tabulation, you must ask
yourself if you are interested in row percentages, column percentages,
or both.
The next step is to calculate the expected frequencies . These are the
frequencies we would expect to see if the null hypothesis was true; in
other words, if participating in the retention program made no differ-
ence to the graduation rate of the students. An expected frequency is
calculated for each cell in the cross-tabulation table by multiplying the
row total for the cell by the column total for the cell and then dividing
by the grand total or the total sample size ( n ). The formula looks like
this:

The chi-square statistic looks at differences between the expected and
observed frequencies in each cell. The formula for calculating the chi-

80 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
You can see from the way this statistic is calculated that the chi-square
value is affected by the differences between the expected and observed
frequencies. The larger the differences between the expected and observed
frequencies, the larger the chi-square value will be. You can also see, how-
ever, that the chi-square value is affected by the number of cells or the
number of categories in each of the two variables. The more cells in the
table, the higher you can expect the chi-square value to be, regardless of
whether the difference between the observed and frequencies are large
or small. This is true simply because there are more values being added
together to determine the chi-square value. Therefore, the chi-square
value must be evaluated based on the number of categories in each of
the variables.
This is where we will introduce degrees of freedom . In most sta-
tistical tests, the degrees of freedom must be calculated and taken into
consideration when evaluating the test outcome. Degrees of freedom are
de ned in statistical terms as the number of values involved in the nal
calculation of a statistic that are free to vary. The degrees of freedom for
the chi-square statistic is equal to the number of rows (or number of
categories in one variable) minus 1 times the number of columns (or
number of categories in the other variable) minus 1. This gives us the
number of frequencies we would have to know before we could deter-
mine the frequencies for the rest of the cells. For a 2 2 table such as the
one in our example, the degrees of freedom would be (2 1) (2 1) =
1. In a 3 3 table, the degrees of freedom would be (3 1) (3 1) = 4.
In other statistical tests that use individual values rather than categorical
frequencies, the degrees of freedom are calculated based on sample size
(n ) rather than the number of categories.
Determining the p Value
Once you know the expected and observed frequencies and the degrees
of freedom, you can calculate the p value associated with your chi-square
value. The p value that is associated with the chi-square test indicates the
probability that the differences between the expected and observed fre-
quencies could be the result of sampling error. You calculate the p value
by looking at a table of critical values for chi-square (go to the website
http://www.statsoft.com/textbook/distribution-tables/for an example
chi-square table). Remember that our example is based on a one-tailed
Bivariate Statistical Methods 81
research hypothesis ( The students participating in the new retention pro-
gram are more likely to graduate high school than those students who receive
traditional counseling at the school ). Our chi-square value is 4.97 and the
degree of freedom is 1. Now we can go to the table to determine the p
value. Look at the rst column on the left and locate the degrees of free-
dom ( df ). Because it is 1, we need to look at the values on the rst line.
Continue across the line until you nd the value that is larger than our
chi-square value (4.97). Our value falls between 3.84 and 5.02. To deter-
mine the p value, we need to look across the top row of p values. Our
chi-square value falls between the value corresponding to p = .025 and
p = .05, therefore we know the actual p values lies between .025 and .05.
The way this is presented is p < .05. In other words, you select the larger
of the two p values and state that the p value for your test is less than that
p value. If the chi-square value had been larger than the last value in the
row for df = 1 (7.88), we would have presented the p value as p < .005.
On the other hand, if the chi-square value had been smaller than the rst
value in the row for df = 1 (.00004), we would have presented the p value
as p > .995.
Interpreting and Presenting the Results
Suppose in our example that we have chosen the traditional rejection
level = .05. Based on our ndings, can we reject the null hypothesis?
Before we make this decision, we must consider one more thing. The
chi-square test determines the probability that the relationship between
the two variables could be caused by sampling error. In our example,
this probability is less than .05 suggesting that we can indeed reject the
null hypothesis. But, the chi-square statistic only looks at the difference
between expected and observed. It does not consider the direction of the
difference. In other words, because we are testing a one-tailed or direc-
tional hypothesis, we must check to make sure the difference is in the
desired direction. The chi-square test would show the same relationship
whether the students in the retention groups had a higher graduation
rate or a lower graduation rate than the students who received the tra-
ditional services. Looking at the data, we can see that the students in the
retention groups had a higher graduation rate than the control students;
therefore, the differences identi ed by the chi-square statistic are in the
desired direction. We can, therefore, safely reject the null hypothesis
82 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
based on a p value of less than .05. In cases where a two-tailed or nondi-
rectional research hypothesis is being tested, this last step can be omitted
because any statistically signi cant difference found would support our
research hypothesis.
When presenting the results from a chi-square statistical analysis,
three values must be presented: the chi-square value itself (
2
), degrees
of freedom ( df ), and the probability that sampling error could have pro-
duced the differences between observed and expected frequencies ( p) . In
our example, the results would be presented as follows:
2
= 4.97, df = 1, p < .05
Another way these results can be represented is:
>
2
(1)
= 4.97; p < .05]
Examples of Chi-Square Test in the Literature
Use of the chi-square test can be found throughout the social service litera-
ture. Chapman, Desai, Falzer, and Borum (2006) used chi-square analyses
to examine the risk and protective factors of 757 juvenile offenders admit-
ted to youth detention centers. A chi-square test revealed that African
American youths were more likely than White youths to be detained for
serious offenses that were transferred automatically to adult court. While
African American youths were more likely to come from disorganized,
highly violent neighborhoods, they were less likely to score high on the
drug or alcohol use scales, and less likely to show a high risk of violence.
These were partially explained by the higher level of protective factors
found among the African American youths, including stronger attach-
ments and bonds and more engagement in socially acceptable pursuits.
The chi-square test is also used to determine if a research sample is
representative of the larger population with regard to some characteristic
that is measured at the nominal or ordinal level. For example, in this
same study, Chapman et al. (2006) noted that the distribution of race in
the youth offenders was not representative of race in the population of
the state in which the study was conducted, with African American and
Hispanic youths overrepresented and White youths underrepresented in
the detention center.
Bivariate Statistical Methods 83
In another study (McClatchey, Vonk, & Palardy, 2009), the effective-
ness of a camp-based, trauma-focused grief intervention was examined.
The sample included 100 children who had lost a parent, and the treat-
ment focused on reducing traumatic grief and posttraumatic stress dis-
order symptoms among the children. The results from the chi-square test
revealed that children who did not attend the camp were much more
likely to continue experiencing severe PTSD symptoms than children
who did attend the camp. In addition, the chances of experiencing severe
grief were much greater for children who did not attend the camp.
Chi-square analysis is also used to compare an experimental group
with the control or comparison group to determine whether the groups
are equivalent on characteristics that have been deemed important by
the researcher. In this study (McClatchey et al., 2009), chi-square tests
were used to ascertain that the two groups were equivalent with regard to
gender, race, age group, type of loss (mother or father), and type of death
(expected or unexpected).
In addition to comparing two groups based on whether the partici-
pants completed a treatment (experimental group) or not (comparison
group), the chi-square test is also used to compare variables of inter-
est based on the attributes of a dichotomous variable. For example,
Myers (2010) looked at drug, alcohol, and tobacco use, and use of vio-
lence among adolescents in a rural, southern community, based on race
(Caucasian versus African American), gender (male versus female), and
age (middle schoolaged children versus high schoolaged children). She
studied more than 2,500 middle and high school youth, and concluded
that Caucasian youth were more likely to use tobacco and alcohol, while
African American students were more likely to engage in violent activi-
ties. Male students were more likely to use tobacco and drugs than female
students, and were more likely to engage in violent activities. Finally,
older students were more likely to use tobacco, alcohol, and drugs, and to
participate in violent behaviors than younger students.
Using SPSS
In this demonstration we explain how to conduct the chi-square test in
SPSS, version 19. The Chi-Square test is used to evaluate signi cant dif-
ferences between groups, such as differences in diagnosis between males
and females. The chi-square test can only be conducted with categorical
84 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
data, measured at the nominal or ordinal level. In this example, we use two
categorical variables from the NELS data set, SEX and DROPOUT_RISK.
SEX is an indicator of the sex of the respondent. The value of 1 indicates
male and the value 2 indicates female. DROPOUT_RISK indicates
the number of risk factors that each respondent has for dropping out of
school. The value 0 indicates that the respondent has no risk factors; the
value 1 indicates that the respondent has one or more risk factors.

Alternatives to the Chi-square Statistical Test
Technically, the chi-square test can be used for variables measured at
the nominal or ordinal levels. However, it is generally agreed that the
Bivariate Statistical Methods 85
chi-square test should not be used with ordinal-level data, because the
test ignores the ranking of the different categories. Alternative nonpara-
metric tests, such as the MannWhitney U, the Median test, and the
KruskalWallis test, are alternatives to the chi-square test when consider-
ing ordinal-level data (Krysik & Finn, 2010).
Sample size is another consideration when deciding whether to use
the chi-square test. In order to use the chi-square test, the sample size
must be large enough so that the expected frequency in each cell is at least
5. If your sample size is small, you can combine cells (when appropriate)
in order to increase the expected frequencies in each cell. In cases where
the frequency for one or more of the cells is less than 5 and the cells can-
not be collapsed, another statistical test, the Fisher exact test , may be used
to determine the relationship between the two variables.
t TESTS
In social work research, the IV is often measured at the nominal level. For
example, we may be comparing an experimental group to a control group
or a wait-listed comparison group. Or we may want to compare two or
more groups based on some demographic characteristic, such as gender,
race, or sexual orientation. In cases where the DV is also at the nominal
or ordinal level, we would use the chi-square test or one of the alternatives
discussed earlier. However, when the DV is measured at the interval or ratio
level, which is often the case, we would turn to t tests and simple analysis of
variance (also referred to as simple ANOVA or one-way ANOVA).
The t test is used when the IV is dichotomous (nominal with only two
categories) and the DV is measured at the interval or ratio level. When
the IV has more than two categories, the simple ANOVA must be used.
The t test is a parametric statistical test, and therefore should meet the
general requirements of parametric procedures. We describe three basic
forms of the t test in detail: the one-sample t test, the dependent-samples
t test, and the independent-samples t test.
One-Sample t Test
The one-sample t test compares the mean of the DV (interval or ratio
level) for the research sample to the known or estimated mean of the
86 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
population from which the sample was drawn. It is used to determine
if the sample is typical of the population with regard to the DV, or if it
differs signi cantly from the population. The known or estimated popu-
lation mean is called the test value. The formula for this test produces a
value for t, and then the researcher must refer to a table of critical values
using the t value and the degrees of freedom to nd the p value. The cal-
culation for degrees of freedom for a one-sample t test is the sample size
(n ) minus 1.
The one-sample t test is used for two general purposes. The rst is
to determine if the sample drawn from a population is representative
of the population in relation to some important interval or ratio-level
variable. For example, suppose we are conducting a study to determine
if gender is related to scores on a standardized instrument measuring
self-esteem among students in our high school. We select a sample of
30 students from the high school, and we would like our sample to
be representative of the population of all students on the variable age,
a variable that we suspect might be a confounding variable affecting
self-esteem. We would calculate the one-sample t test by comparing the
mean age of the sample to the mean age of all of the students at the
high school. In this case, we would actually hope for a large p value.
A large p value would indicate that the mean age of the sample is not
statistically different from the mean age of the population. Therefore,
we could continue our study with this sample. A small p value (i.e., less
than .05) would indicate that the mean age of the sample is statistically
different from the mean age of the population, therefore we might draw
another sample.
The second purpose of the one-sample t test is to determine if
a research sample differs from the population on some interval or
ratio-level variable to the extent that the difference is not likely caused
by sampling error. This same test can be used in situations in which we
hope to see a signi cant difference between our sample and the greater
population, such as in cases where our sample has completed some inter-
vention that we hypothesize will signi cantly change their score on some
interval or ratio-level measurement.
For example, suppose you are trying to determine if the students
attending your communitys magnet program in the arts differ from the
larger population on an IQ test. You already know that the average IQ
score is 100, so 100 is set as the test value. If you are hypothesizing that
Bivariate Statistical Methods 87
these students IQ scores will be higher than the average population IQ
score, your one-tailed research hypothesis would read:
The mean IQ score for the students involved in the magnet program is
higher than the mean population IQ score of 100.
The corresponding null hypothesis would read:
The mean IQ score for the students involved in the magnet program does
not differ from the mean population IQ score of 100.
Suppose we select 30 students from the magnet program and complete
an IQ test with each student. The mean of these IQ scores is 108 and
the standard deviation is 6. We now have all the information we need to
calculate the value of t and determine if there is support for our research
hypothesis. The formula for calculating the value of t for the one-sample
t test looks like this:
t

Therefore, the t value is 7.34. Next we must locate the p value to deter-
