by sampling error.
To nd the p value, we need to refer to a table showing the t distribution
(go to the website http://www.statsoft.com/textbook/distribution-tables/
for an example t table). Because the sample size is 30 in this example,
the degrees of freedom would be 29 ( n 1). Look down the column of
degrees of freedom until you reach 29. Then move across the row of g-
ures until you nd where 7.34 falls. Our calculated t value is larger than
the value in the last column, therefore our p value is less than .0005.
88 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
Because p < .0005, there is almost no chance that sampling error can
explain the difference between the samples mean IQ score and the popu-
lations mean score. Therefore, we would reject the null hypothesis. The
results would be presented as follows:
t = 7.34, df = 29, p < .0005 or [t (29) = 7.34; p < .0005]
Examples of one-sample t test in the literature. The one-sample
t test is used in the social science literature to compare data from a
research sample to known population data. One study by Kim, Szatmari,
Bryson, Streiner, and Wilson (2000) looked at the prevalence of mood
and anxiety issues among children with Asperger Syndrome and autism.
The researchers used the one-sample t test to compare the scores of the
children in the sample on several measures with population norms that
had already been established for these measures. They concluded that
the children with autism and Asperger Syndrome scored signi cantly
higher than the population means on depressive, overanxious, ADHD,
and oppositional behaviors. They did not score signi cantly higher than
population means on conduct disorder or separation anxiety.
Kagee (2008) studied 119 patients being treated for diabetes or
hypertension to determine if these patients were more likely to experi-
ence symptoms of depression and anxiety than the general population.
Kagee compared patient scores on measures of anxiety and depression to
the cut-point score that had already been established to determine clini-
cal signi cance, and found that the sample mean did not differ signi -
cantly from the cut-point score. The results did, however, suggest that a
signi cant number of patients were experiencing signi cant psychologi-
cal dif culties for which they may not have been receiving treatment.
Alternatives to the One-Sample t Test. If the DV is measured at the
nominal or ordinal level, the chi-square test would be used instead of
the one-sample t test to accomplish the same thing. The chi-square test
would be used, for example, if you wanted to determine if your sample
was representative of the population with regard to race, marital status,
or some other categorical variable.
Dependent Samples t Test
The dependent samples or paired-samples t test is used to determine if
there is a statistically signi cant difference between the scores from two
Bivariate Statistical Methods 89
samples in which the individual values or cases in the sample are paired
with each other for some reason related to the research question being
asked. Three examples of when two samples of data may be dependent
(i.e., paired) are:
Individual cases in two different groups are sometimes paired
with each other, either naturally (such as twins) or based on some
characteristic. Both groups are then measured on some interval
or ratio-level variable and the values are compared across each
pair in the sample.
One sample of cases that have been measured on some interval
or ratio-level variable two times, such as in a pretest and posttest
outcome study.
In some situations, two different, but related, scores will be
compared to each other for one sample of cases (such as
comparing reading and writing scores from some standardized
test).
In each of these instances, we have a series of paired values to put into
the formula. The degrees of freedom for a dependent-samples t test is the
number of pairs of values minus 1. When one sample is being measured
two times, the degrees of freedom are equal to the sample size minus 1.
When two groups have been paired up and measured one time, degrees
of freedom are equal to the number of pairs of cases minus 1.
Paired Samples Measured One Time. In this situation, two groups
or samples have been matched one-to-one based on some characteristic.
For example, in twin studies, the twins are paired with one twin being
in one group and the second twin being in the second group. In other
examples, we may want to match group members on some variable we
believe could be a confounding variable to ensure that the in uence of
the confounding variable is controlled. See Table 4.5 for an example of
two samples that have been matched as closely as possible on the variable,
age, and measured on the DV, self-esteem level.
One Sample Measured Two Times. In this situation, one sample is
measured two times on an interval or ratio-level DV. Research studies
that involve only one sample measured at pretest and posttest would
use the dependent-samples t test to determine if there was a statistically
signi cant change between the two administrations of the measure. See
90 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
Table 4.6 for an example of one sample measured two times on the DV,
self-esteem level.

sample size of 30 or more. We are using a smaller sample size simply for
convenience in presenting the calculations. The formula for the depen-

difference between two means and accompanying con dence intervals.
Examples of dependent samples t test in the literature. The
dependent-samples t test can be found throughout the social science lit-
erature. The most common use is comparing pretest and posttest data.
Singh et al. (2007) looked at the effects of mindfulness training for par-
ents of children with autism. Comparing pretest and posttest measures of
parental aggressive behaviors, the researchers discovered that the aggres-
sive behaviors were signi cantly reduced and the childrens social skills
had increased after mindfulness training was completed. In addition, the
parents were more satis ed with their parenting, reported more social
interaction with their children, and experienced less parenting stress.
Bivariate Statistical Methods 93
A study by Wang, Blomberg, and Li (2005) provides an example of
how the dependent-samples t test can be used to test one measure across
two samples that have been matched based on some characteristic deemed
important by the researcher. In this study, a sample of delinquent youth
was paired with nondelinquent youth based on age, race, gender, socio-
economic status, exceptionality status, and school type. The matched pairs
were then compared in terms of academic achievement, school atten-
dance, and disciplinary problems. By comparing each delinquent youth to
a nondelinquent youth who was equivalent with regard to age, race, and
the other control variables, the researchers were able to determine if delin-
quency and academic de ciencies were related. Wang et al. (2005) used the
dependent-samples t test to compare 5,187 matched pairs of adolescents,
and found that the delinquent youth were more likely to suffer from educa-
tional de ciencies than the nondelinquent comparison youth. The delin-
quent adolescents were more likely to have lower grade point averages and
lower attendance rates, had signi cantly more disciplinary problems, and
were more likely to be retained and have to repeat grades in school.

data set, BY2XRSTD and BY2XMSTD. BY2XRSTD provides a measure
of standardized reading scores and BY2XMSTD provides a measure of
standardized math scores.

Independent-Samples t test
Finally, the independent-samples t test compares the mean scores on an
interval or ratio-level DV between two independent groups. For exam-
ple, this test would be used to compare scores between an experimental
group and a control group, or between a sample of females and a sample
of males. The sample size for the two groups does not have to be equal.
The degrees of freedom for the independent-samples t test equals the
total sample size of the two groups combined minus 2.
Example. Suppose a group of 21 new employees are scheduled to
participate in a preparation class before taking an exam to measure their
understanding of agency policies. Remember again that we are using a
smaller than customary sample size in order to present the example. In an
effort to evaluate a new on-line preparation course, the supervisor ran-
domly assigns 10 employees to complete the traditional face-to-face class
and 11 employees to complete the new on-line course. The supervisor
is con dent that the traditional class will be more effective in preparing
the employees, because he feels the personal contact and the opportu-
nity to ask questions throughout the presentation are vital to helping the
employees understand the policies. He wants data to help him argue that
the traditional courses should continue to be taught. He believes that if
the outcome of the group completing the on-line course is as good as or
better than the group completing the traditional course, the traditional
course will be cancelled because the on-line course is cheaper and easier
to administer. Therefore, he writes his hypothesis as follows:
The employees who complete the traditional face-to-face preparation course
will score higher on the exam than those employees who complete the on-
line preparation course.
Bivariate Statistical Methods 95

(see Table 4.8 for data and calculations). The mean for the traditional
course is 89.7 and the mean for the on-line course is 78.1. The inde-
pendent-samples t test can be used to determine if there is a statistically
signi cant difference between these two means, or if sampling error can
more plausibly account for this amount of variation. The formula for cal-
culating the value of t for two independent samples with different sample
sizes and equal variances is:

The value of t is 3.59. Looking at the table of critical values of t (go to the
website http://www.statsoft.com/textbook/distribution-tables/for an exam-
ple t table), you can locate the p value. Degrees of freedom are equal to the
Bivariate Statistical Methods 97
sum of the two samples sizes (21) minus 2, which equals 19. Look down the
column of df until you get to 19. Then look across the row of values until you
nd the largest value that is still smaller than 3.59. In this case, that number
is 2.861 (the next number, 3.883, is larger than our t value). The p value that
is directly above 2.861 is .005. Therefore, our p value is less than .005.
If we set our rejection level at < .05, then we would reject the null
hypothesis and conclude that the employees that completed the in-person
class scored statistically signi cantly higher on the evaluation than the
employees that completed the on-line course. Therefore, the supervi-
sor can reject the null hypothesis and argue that the employees learn the
policies better when taking the in-person class. This statistic would be
presented as follows: t = 3.59, df = 19, p < .005 or [ t (19) = 3.59; p <
.005]. Once again, this indicates that the averages of the two groups are
statistically different from one another, but does not indicate the size of
the difference. An effect-size measure can be calculated to determine the
size or magnitude of the difference.
Examples of independent samples t test in the literature.
Independent-samples t tests are used throughout the research literature to
compare variables of interest between experimental and control groups.
Lev-Wiesel and Liraz (2007) analyzed the narrative descriptions of negative
life events given by 60 children whose fathers were drug abusers to deter-
mine if drawing prior to the narratives added richness to the descriptions
given. Each child in the experimental group was asked to draw his or her life
in the shadow of their fathers addiction to drugs. They were then asked to
verbally describe their life in the same shadow. The children in the compar-
ison group were asked only to verbally describe their lives. The researchers
concluded that the narratives of the children who had rst drawn their lives
were more detailed and more revealing of emotions than the narratives of
those children who had not drawn prior to providing their narratives.
The independent-samples t test can also be used to compare a sample
across the attributes of a dichotomous variable, such as gender. Rayle
et al. (2006) examined the gender differences among American Indian
middle school students with regard to frequency of drug offers and dif-
culty in refusing drugs from various people who offer the drugs. They
found that the female students reported more offers of illegal drugs from
friends, cousins, and other peers than the male students. The female stu-
dents also reported more dif culty in responding to and refusing drug
offers from all sources.
98 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
In addition, like the chi-square test, the independent samples t test is
also used to determine the equivalence of two groups in a research study.
While the chi-square is used to compare groups based on nominal and
ordinal-level variables, the t test is used to compare groups based on interval
and ratio-level variables. For example, before looking at the gender differ-
ences, Rayle et al. (2006) rst used the independent-samples t test to deter-
mine that the males were not signi cantly different from the females with
regard to age or grade level. They used the chi-square test to verify equiva-
lency on nominal variables, such as whether or not students lived on a reser-
vation and whether they received free or reduced-priced school lunch.

Independent Samples t Tests in SPSS, version 19. The Independent Samples
t Test is used to determine whether there is a signi cant difference between
mean scores of two groups, such as a difference between males and females
on their mean level of depression. One variable must be dichotomous;
the other variable should be measured at the interval or ratio level. In this
example, we use SEX for the dichotomous variable and BY2XRSTD, for
the ratio level variable. SEX is an indicator of the sex of the respondent.
The value of 1 indicates male and the value 2 indicates female.
BY2XRSTD provides a measure of standardized reading scores.

Bridge to Advanced Statistical Tests
There is a family of statistical procedures that is related to the t test. The
simple or one-way analysis of variance (simple ANOVA) is used much
like the independent-samples t test to compare one IV measured at the
nominal or ordinal level and one DV measured at the interval or ratio
level. Unlike the t test, however, the simple ANOVA can compare the DV
across more than two groups. In other words, the IV does not have to
be dichotomous. The two-way (two IVs) or multifactor (two or more
IVs) ANOVA is used when there is one DV being compared across more
than one IV. The multiple analysis of variance (MANOVA) is used when
there are more than one DV measured at the interval or ratio level. The
one-factor MANOVA is used when there is one IV and more than one
DV, and the multifactor MANOVA is used when there are multiple IVs
and multiple DVs.
One step further is the analysis of covariance (ANCOVA), also
known as the univariate general linear model (GLM). The ANCOVA
allows the researcher to examine the differences in one DV across two
or more categorical IVs, while controlling for the effects of one or more
extraneous variables on the DV. These extraneous variables are called
covariates. The ANCOVA identi es the difference between the groups
on the DV after adjusting for the effects of the covariates or control
variables. Chapter 6 will look more closely at this family of statistical
procedures.
CORRELATION
While the chi-square test of association examined earlier looks at
whether two variables measured at the nominal or ordinal-level are
100 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
associated with one another, correlation analyses are often used to
examine the association between variables measured at the interval or
ratio level. Correlation analyses can determine the strength of the rela-
tionship between two variables, the direction of the relationship, and
the probability that the relationship between the two variables might be
due to sampling error. The strength of the relationship is determined by
looking at the extent to which the values of the two variables co-vary. If
we determine that they do co-vary, the direction signi es whether the
values of one variable tend to move in the same direction as the val-
ues of the second variable, or whether they tend to move in opposite
directions. We can nd the p value to determine the chance that this
relationship is strong enough that we can assume it cannot be explained
by sampling error.
Correlation analyses are used for a variety of purposes in research.
In descriptive research, correlation analyses can determine the strength
of the relationship between two variables of interest with regard to the
sample or population being studied. For example, we may want to nd
out if the number of hours students work while they are completing
their college education is signi cantly related to their overall grade
point average in school. Or, we might want to verify that a higher rate
of absenteeism from school is signi cantly related to overall grade point
average.
In cases where the correlation between two variables has been shown
to be very strong, the value of one variable can be used to predict the
value of the second variable. Suppose, for example, that we determine
that number of drug arrests in a community has been shown to strongly
correlate to the age that an adolescent living in that community will rst
experiment with illicit drugs. The correlation is a negative one, with the
higher the number of drug arrests being associated with a younger age of
drug experimentation. Social workers could then predict that adolescents
living in neighborhoods with high drug arrests may be at high risk for
drug use, and could target these neighborhoods for appropriate preven-
tion programs.
Correlation analyses are also used extensively in the development
of measurement instruments. They can be used to identify individual
questions in an instrument that are weakly correlated to the instru-
ment as a whole, and may, therefore, be deleted from the instrument to
reduce its length. Correlation is also used to calculate the reliability of
Bivariate Statistical Methods 101
measurement instruments, including inter-rater reliability, testretest
reliability, parallel-forms reliability, and split-half reliability.
Displaying Correlations through Scattergrams
Bivariate correlation analyses are most often used to analyze the linear
correlation between two variables. Bivariate correlation shows whether
the values of the two variables tend to co-vary in the same direction or in
opposite directions across all of the values in the sample. In other words, do
the values of the rst variable tend to increase as the values of the second
variable increase or do the values of the rst variable tend to increase as the
values of the second variable decrease? The extent to which these values
co-vary consistently across the entire population or sample determines the
strength of the linear correlation. Look again at the example scattergrams
shown in Figures 4.1, 4.2, and 4.3. Figure 4.1 suggests that higher levels of
depression are associated with higher levels of disordered eating behaviors,
and lower levels of depression are associated with lower levels of disordered
eating behaviors. This suggests a positive linear correlation , as the val-
ues of the variables are moving in the same direction. Note in the scatter-
gram, when a line is drawn through the center of the values, it angles from
the lower left to the upper right. Figure 4.2 suggests that higher levels of
depression are associated with lower levels of disordered eating behaviors,
and lower levels of depression are associated with higher levels of disor-
dered eating behaviors. This suggests a negative linear correlation , since
the values now move in opposite directions. On the scattergram, when a
line is drawn through the center of the values, it angles from the upper left
to the lower right.
Finally, Figure 4.3 suggests little or no correlation between levels of
depression and disordered eating behaviors. The values of the two vari-
ables do not co-vary in either direction. The line drawn through the cen-
ter of the values tends to be a straight horizontal line.
A perfect positive correlation is when the values of the rst variable
move not only in the same direction, but in the exact same amount.
A perfect negative correlation is when the values of the two variables
move in opposite directions, but in the exact same amount. A scatter-
gram displaying a perfect correlation would therefore be a completely
straight line. Obviously, variables that have perfect correlations would
be rare, and because they move in exactly the same or exactly opposite
102 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
ways, they would be of little interest to the researcher. Social work
researchers are much more interested in variables that have nonperfect
correlations.
Correlation Coef cients
While scattergrams provide a way of displaying the relationship between
two variables, they can only provide an estimation of the strength of the
relationship. In order to calculate the exact strength and statistical signi -
cance of the relationship, the correlation coef cient must be determined.
The correlation coef cient provides a numerical indicator of both the
strength and the direction of the relationship between the paired values
of two interval or ratio-level variables. Because the correlation coef cient
provides information about the strength or magnitude of the relation-
ship between the variables, it is considered to be a measure of effect size.
There are several different formulas that can be used to calculate the
correlation coef cient, the most common of which is Pearsons prod-
uct moment correlation coef cient , or Pearsons r . The values of the
Pearsons r correlation coef cient, expressed as r, can range from 1.0,
signifying a perfect negative linear correlation, to +1.0, signifying a
perfect positive linear correlation. A correlation coef cient of 0 using
Pearsons r indicates no linear correlation or relationship between the
variables at all. Note that the plus sign is usually not displayed before
a positive correlation coef cient. The positive nature of the correlation
is implied. We want to point out that Pearsons r only considers linear
correlations between variables. If two variables are related in a nonlinear
fashion, another type of analysis would need to be used.
The closer the value of the coef cient is to +1.0, the stronger the
positive correlation between the two variables. The closer the value is to
1.0, the stronger the negative correlation. The closer the value is to 0, the
weaker the correlation between the variables. It is important to under-
stand that negative correlations are not inherently weaker than positive
correlations. It simply indicates that the values co-vary in opposite direc-
tions rather than in the same direction. For example, a correlation of
.42 and a correlation of .42 indicate correlations of exactly the same
strength. A correlation of .64 is stronger than a correlation of .39.
Cohen (1988) has developed a system for interpreting the strength
of a linear correlation based on the Pearsons r correlation coef cient.
Bivariate Statistical Methods 103
He suggests that a correlation coef cient greater than or equal to .1 but
less than .3 is a weak correlation, a correlation greater than or equal to .3
but less than .5 is a moderate correlation, and a correlation greater than
or equal to .5 is a strong correlation. If your correlation coef cient is
negative, simply use the absolute value of the correlation coef cient to
interpret the strength of the correlation using Cohens system.
It is important to point out that even a very strong correlation between
two variables does not indicate that the values of one of the variables
actually cause the values of the second variable. A third variable could be
responsible for causing the values of both of these variables, hence the
common phrase, correlation does not equal causation. If, however, it is
determined that one variable has a causal relationship with another vari-
able, these variables must also be correlated with one another.
Determining statistical signi cance. In addition to looking at the
strength and direction of a linear correlation, we can also determine if
the strength of the correlation between two variables can be explained
by sampling error. Using the correlation coef cient and the sample
size, we can identify the p value to determine if the correlation between
the two variables is statistically signi cant. Sample size is an important
factor when determining the statistical signi cance of a correlation. A
strong correlation of, say, .62, might not be statistically signi cant with
a small sample size, because sampling error may be able to explain
the relationship. On the other hand, a weak correlation, for example
.25, might be statistically signi cant with a large sample size, because
although the correlation is a weak one, the relationship between the
variables could not be explained by sampling error. Therefore, it is
important to look at the strength and direction of a correlation, in
addition to its statistical signi cance, when interpreting the outcome
of a correlation analysis.
Example. Suppose we want to calculate the strength and direction of
the correlation between the number of previous arrests and the number
of months to which a group of adolescent males have been sentenced
to serve in the juvenile detention center. In this example, our one-tailed
hypothesis could read:

of adolescent males have been sentenced to serve in the juvenile detention
center is positively correlated.

Coef cient of Determination
The coef cient of determination , expressed as r
2
, can be determined by
squaring the correlation coef cient r . This value indicates the proportion
of the variation in one of the variables that is related to (or can poten-
tially be explained by) the values of the second variable. For example,
suppose the correlation between the number of previous arrests and the
number of months to which juvenile offenders are sentenced is .6, the
coef cient of determination would be .6
2
or .36. This value indicates that
about 36% of variation in the sentencing is related to or can be explained
by the number of previous arrests. The remaining 64% of the variation
is assumed to be related to other variables or error related to the research
design.
106 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
Examples of Correlations in the Literature
Correlational analyses are used extensively throughout social science
research. Kelly, Warner, Trahan, and Miscavage (2009) examined the cor-
relation between level of depression and level of psychological abuse in a
sample of 100 women, and found a signi cant positive correlation between
level of depression and level of total abuse (emotional, verbal, physical, and
sexual), as well as subscale scores of emotional and verbal abuse.
In another study, Clark, Skouteris, Wertheim, Paxton, and Milgrom
(2009) looked at the relationship between depression and body dissat-
isfaction during pregnancy and the rst 12 months postpartum. The
researchers found a positive correlation between depression and body
dissatisfaction measures and a negative correlation between a depression
scale and subscales measuring attractiveness and feelings of strength and
tness. These correlations were strongest at six weeks and six months
postpartum when women experienced the most body dissatisfaction.
Correlation is also commonly used when measuring the validity and
reliability of measurement instruments. Balfour et al. (2007) used cor-
relation to develop and validate the HIV Medication Readiness Scale . This
scale assesses the clients psychological readiness for successfully utiliz-
ing and adhering to HIV medications. The researchers used correlational
analyses to determine that the 10-item instrument demonstrated high
internal consistency, testretest reliability, and sensitivity to change.
Other methods were used to assess content validity, convergent validity,
and predictive validity.

ple, we use two ratio-level variables from the NELS data set, BY2XRSTD
and BY2XMSTD. BY2XRSTD provides a measure of standardized reading
scores and BY2XMSTD provides a measure of standardized math scores.

Nonlinear Correlations
In this section, we have focused on linear correlations. As noted previ-
ously, Pearsons r only considers linear correlations between variables.
There are, however, other types of correlation, such as cyclical correlations
and curvilinear correlation. A nonlinear correlation would be found when
the values of two variables co-vary, but do not continuously vary in the
same direction for the entire sample or population. A scattergram dis-
playing a cyclical correlation would look like a series of waves. The values
16

Figure 4.4 Scattergram Showing a Curvilinear Correlation.
108 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
of the two variables would alternate moving in the same direction, then
moving in opposite directions, etc. A scattergram displaying a curvilinear
correlation would form a U shape or an upside-down U shape or arch.
For example, the scattergram in Figure 4.4 shows a curvilinear correla-
tion between the amount of time a faculty advisor may spend with their
student and the number of credit hours completed by the students.
The graph suggests that when juniors (students with 60 credit hours)
rst enter a social work program, the faculty advisor spends a signi -
cant amount of time with the student. During the second semester of the
junior year and the rst semester of the senior year (credit hours from
75105), the faculty advisor tends to spend less time with the student.
During the last semester of the program, when students may be complet-
ing their internship and are preparing for graduation, the hours spent
advising increase. These two variables are clearly correlated; however, it
is not a linear correlation.
Alternatives to the Pearsons r Correlation
The Pearsons r should only be used in cases where the requirements for a
parametric statistical test are met. There are alternative statistical tests, such
as Spearmans rho and Kendalls tau, that can be used when the variables are
measured at the ordinal-level or when the data are not normally distributed.
For example, suppose we want to determine the correlation between socio-
economic level and client satisfaction level. Either of these alternative tests
could be used to calculate the correlation coef cient. Like the Pearsons r, the
Spearmans rho and Kendalls tau both have a table of values that must be
used to determine whether the correlation is statistically signi cant.
Bridge to Advanced Statistical Tests
In some situations, it is important to consider the correlation between
three or more variables. Multivariate correlation analyses examine the
correlation between one outcome variable and several predictor variables.
One example is the multiple correlation (multiple R). It combines the val-
ues of the predictor variables to determine the strength of the correlation
between these values and the values of the outcome variable. There are
other multivariate analyses that use correlation in their calculations, such
as factor analysis and cluster analysis.
109
5
Bivariate and
Multivariate Linear
Regression Analysis
INTRODUCTION
Linear regression analysis is a set of statistical procedures designed
to examine relationships between one or more independent vari-
ables (IV) and one dependent (i.e., outcome) variable (DV). In linear
regression, the DV is always measured at the interval or ratio level.
For example, Schiff and Levit (2010) used linear-regression analy-
sis to assess the relationship between the IVs of trauma history and
therapeutic alliance between Israeli social workers and female clients
receiving methadone treatment and the DV of reduced posttraumatic
stress disorder (PTSD). Posttraumatic stress disorder was measured
using the Posttraumatic Diagnostic Scale (PDS) (Foa, Cashman,
Jaycox, & Perry, 1997). The PDS includes 49 items that assess PTSD
symptoms. Responses are measured at the interval level, ranging from
0 to 51.
110 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
Bivariate and Multiple Linear Regression Analysis
Linear regression analysis may involve only one IV or it may involve sev-
eral. Linear regression models with only one IV are referred to as bivari-
ate or simple regression models . Linear regression models with more
than one IV are referred to as multiple linear regression models . In
multiple linear regression analysis, each IV provides its own contribution
in predicting the DV. Thus, the model being predicted is more complex
than with bivariate regression analysis. Multiple linear regression ana-
lytic procedures build on bivariate linear-regression analysis. As such,
multiple linear regression analysis includes additional requirements and
assumptions for running the model, and the interpretation of the results
differ somewhat.
Types of Regression Analysis Methods
There are several different types of regression analysis methods. It is
important to use the method that matches your research question and
the type of data you are analyzing. Linear regression is used when the DV
is measured at the interval or ratio-level. For instance, Horwitz-McCue,
Balestracci, and Simms (2001) used the linear regression method to
examine changes in reported functioning of children in foster care. The
DV was assessed using the Vineland Adaptive Behavioral Scale, (Sparrow
& Cicchetti, 1987) which is an interval-level measure of foster mother
perceptions of foster child adjustment.
Logistic regression is another common regression method. It is used
when the DV is measured as a dichotomous variable, with only two val-
ues. For instance, studies investigating factors that predict foster care
placementthe DVwould apply logistic regression procedures to ana-
lyze the data. In this case, foster care placement is a dichotomous vari-
able, with two valuesplaced into foster care or not. In a real example,
Alexander and others (1997) used logistic-regression methods to exam-
ine the relationship between individual, family, and school IVs and high
school dropout as the DV. High school dropout was assessed as a dichot-
omous variable with two valuesdropped out or not. Linear and logistic
regression procedures are only two of several regression methods avail-
able for analyzing data. The focus in this book is on linear regression. For
more on logistic regression analysis, we recommend Orme and Combs-
Orme (2009) or Kleinbaum and Klein (2010).
Bivariate and Multivariate Linear Regression Analysis 111
Structure of the Chapter
In this chapter, we provide a detailed explanation of linear regression
analysis, covering the relevant basic statistics (i.e., correlation, proper-
ties of a straight line, and variance), sums of squares, model estimation
and t, assumptions and other model requirements, and methods of data
entry. We then describe examples of social work studies that have used
linear regression analysis methods. At the end of the chapter, we pro-
vide step-by-step instructions for conducting linear regression analysis
in SPSS, using data from the National Educational Longitudinal Study
of 1988 (NELS: 88).
LINEAR REGRESSION ANALYSIS: A DETAILED DESCRIPTION
The goal of linear regression analysis is to determine the best model, in
the form of an equation, for predicting values of the DV using the val-
ues of the IVs for each case in the dataset. Of course, the model that we
develop depends on the data that we have. In this context, the goal is to
determine the model that best ts our data. As Tabachnick and Fidell
(2007) state, the intent of linear regression is to arrive at a set of values,
or estimated regression coef cients for each of the IVs that bring the Y
values predicted from the equation as close as possible to the actual Y
values obtained by measurement (p. 128 ) .
In linear regression, the best- tting model is actually represented by
a straight line. This straight line connects the means of the IVs and the
DV in a way that minimizes the sum of the squared distances between
the data points and this line. This will be explained in more detail when
we discuss the properties of a straight line. In bivariate linear regression,
the best- tting straight line is determined by solving the equation for a
straight line, which is Y = + bX + , where,
Y is the DV or the outcome we want to predict from X . The
prime symbol ( ) after Y indicates its predicted rather than actual
value.

crosses the Y -axis (when X = 0).
b (i.e., beta) is the slope of line for Y . Its value represents the
change in Y for each one unit change in X .
112 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
X is the value of the IV that is used to predict Y .
represents the error in the model. Predictions for each case have
associated error. The error represents the difference between
the scores predicted by the line and the scores that are actually
obtained. This will become clearer when we discuss the process
for determining the best tting straight line.

model. The equation is changed to re ect the additional IVs, as follows:

at any level (i.e., nominal, ordinal, interval, and ratio), although it is nec-
essary to recode nominal or ordinal level variables with more than two
values prior to conducting the analysis. We will discuss this in more detail
later in the chapter.
Relevant Basic Statistics in Linear Regression Analysis
Correlation . Linear regression analysis is actually a form of correla-
tion analysis. Recall that correlation analysis produces the Pearson
product-moment correlation coef cient, r . It is used to assess the magni-
tude and direction of the relationship between two variables measured at
the interval or ratio level. Linear regression analysis builds on this, going
beyond simply assessing relationships to actually predicting the value of
the DV from the values of one or more IVs.
The correlation between one IV and one DV in bivariate-regression
analysis is straightforward. On the other hand, in multiple linear regres-
sion analysis there are three types of correlationmultiple correlation,
partial correlation, and semipartial correlation. This is due to having
more than one IV in the model, and thus needing to account for how
they correlate with one another, in addition to their correlation with
the DV. Multiple correlation is the linear correlation between all of the
IVs in the model and the DV. In the context of multiple linear regres-
sion, partial correlation is the unique correlation between one IV and
the DV that is not shared with any of the other IVs. It represents the
Bivariate and Multivariate Linear Regression Analysis 113
extent to which an IV and the DV are associated with one another, while
controlling for the effects of all other IVs on both the DV and the IV. As
Tabachnick and Fidell (1996) state, the contribution of the other IVs
is taken out of both the IV and the DV (p. 157). Semipartial correla-
tion is similar to partial correlation in that it is the unique correlation
between an IV and the DV. However, in this case, the effects of other
IVs are controlled for in either the DV or the IV, but not both. We will
review these correlations in more detail later in the chapter when we
cover estimation procedures.
The straight line in linear regression. The estimation process in linear
regression analysis, referred to as least-squares estimation, involves nd-
ing the straight line that best ts the model to our data. Thus, it is useful
to describe the properties of a straight line. A straight line is de ned by
two featuresits slope and its intercept. The equation for a straight line
is: Y = + bX , where is its intercept and b is its slope. Kleinbaum and oth-
ers (1988, p. 44) present a graph of two straight lines with their respective
equations as a way to explain the properties of a straight line, replicated
in Figure 5.1. To create these lines, arbitrary numbers were selected as
values of and b and then plugged into the straight line equations. For
line y = 4 + ( 2 x ), = 4 and b = 2. This describes a straight line with an
intercept of 4 and a slope of 2. For the line y = 3 + 1 x , = 3 and b = 1
with an intercept of 3 and a slope of 1.
In the straight line equation, the intercept , denoted by , is the point at
which the line crosses the vertical (i.e., Y ) axis of the graph. It is the value
of Y when X equals zero (Keith, 2006). In Figure 5.1, we see that one line
crosses the Y axis at 4, when y = 4 and x = 0. We also see that the other
line crosses the Y axis at 3, when y = 3 and x = 0. Note that this de nition
of the intercept is only true when x = 0. In multiple regression analysis,
the intercept is the mean value of the DV when all of the IVs equal zero
(Keith, 2006).
A lines slope is its gradient or steepness, denoted by b . It represents
the number of unit changes in Y for a one unit change in X . As Kleinbuam
and others (1988) explain, because the line is straight, this rate of change
is always constant. Thus, for the line y = 4 2 x , when x changes one unit,
y changes by minus two units (the value of b , the slope of the line). For
instance, when X changes one unit from 3 to 4, Y changes minus two
units, from 2 [4 2(3)] to 4 [4 2(4)], which is minus two units [( 2) ( 4)
= ( 2) + 4 = 2]. When the value of X changes one unit from 1 to 2, the
114 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
value of Y changes minus two units from 2 [4 2(1)] to 0 [4 2(2)]. The
rate of change is constant.
The sign of a lines slope (either positive or negative) provides infor-
mation about the nature of the relationship between X (the IV) and Y
(the DV). A line that has a slope with a positive value indicates a positive
relationship between X and Y . In other words, as the value of X increases,
so does the value of Y . A line with a negative slope indicates a negative
relationship, such that Y decreases as X increases. Figure 5.1 shows that,
for the line y = 4 2 x , the value of Y decreases as the value of X increases
because the slope is a negative value. The slope of the other line, y = 3 +
1x , is positive and as displayed on the graph, as X increases, Y also
increases.

to determine the best- tting straight line to solve the regression equa-
tion (which is the same equation for a straight line). In linear regres-
sion the least-squares-estimation method is used to nd the best- tting
straight line. This method is used to calculate the slope and intercept as

differences between the predicted and actual data points represent the
error between what we predicted and what we actually obtained. These
differences are referred to as residuals .

The overall pattern of data points suggests that, as spider size increases, so

ues of Y from the values of X . It is the line that ts the data most closely.
What does this mean? We can see that two points fall exactly on the line,
and the rest fall above or below it. In terms of residuals, our interest is in
the points that fall off the line, in particular their vertical distance from

the line. This vertical distance is the difference between the model tted

falls off the line has a vertical-difference value. This value represents the
residual or error from the straight line for that set of points.
The least-squares method of estimating the best- tting straight line
is determined by these residuals (Field, 2005). The values of the residuals
(i.e., their differences) indicate how well the line ts the data. The residual
values of the points that fall above the line are positive. The residual val-
ues of the points that fall below the line are negative. If we simply added
the negative and positive differences together, they would likely cancel
each other out. We can square these differences prior to summing them,
to avoid this. This is referred to as the sum of squared differences . The sum
of squared differences is used to assess the accuracy of our model. The
smaller the value of the sum of squared differences, the more closely the
line represents the data. The least-squares method involves determining
the line that has the lowest sum of squared differences. This is the line
that best represents the actual data.
Sums of Squared Differences
The least-squares-regression method is used to predict the best- tting
regression line to our data. But how well does this line t the data? It
may be the best- tting line, but the t may not be very good. In order to
determine the lines quality of t (i.e., goodness of t ), we compare it to
the basic model (i.e., the mean value of Y ). This indicates the extent to
which the predicted line improves the t, relative to the basic model. The
predicted line should provide a better t to the data, compared to the
basic model. To determine the goodness of t, we compare differences
between the observed data points and the mean value of Y , to the dif-
ferences between observed data points and the predicted regression line.
The basis of this comparison is made from three types of sums of squared
differencestotal sum of squared differences (SS
T
), residual sum of
squared differences (SS
R
), and model sum of squared differences (SS
M
).

to as total sum of squares, residual sum of squares, and model sum of
squares. Field (2005, p. 149) presents a set of three graphs that illustrates
how these sums of squares are determined. These graphs, provided in
Figure 5.3, are described as follows.

R

correlation coef cient) indicates the correlation between the predicted
and actual values of the DV. In other words, R provides a measure of the
degree to which the set of IVs together correlates with the DV. In mul-
tiple regression analysis we wish to know the proportion of variance in
the DV that is explained by the IVs. The multiple correlation coef cient,
120 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
squared (i.e., the coef cient of multiple determination, or R
2
) provides a

In determining the correlation between a set of IVs and a DV, it is
necessary to account for the potential correlation between the IVs them-
selves. Otherwise, the total correlation will be greater than 100%. For
example, consider the study by Nasim, Belgrave, Corona, and Townsend
(2009) designed to determine factors that predict alcohol-refusal atti-
tudes among teenagers. The DV is alcohol-refusal attitudes and the IVs
are lifetime alcohol use, number of alcohol-using peers, and number of
tobacco-using peers. For the purpose of explaining why it is necessary to
account for overlapping correlation between IVs, we assume that bivariate
correlation analyses between each IV and the DV indicate the following
correlation coef cients: r = .60 for lifetime alcohol use; r = .80 for number
of alcohol-using peers, and r = .55 for number of tobacco-using peers. To
determine the proportion of variance in the DV that is explained by these
IVs, we calculate the coef cient of multiple determination ( R
2
), which is
simply the value of R , squared. In this case, the values of R
2
for each of the
IVs are: .36, .64, and .30. The sum of these values is 1.30, which exceeds
100%. This is an example of what happens when we fail to account for
the overlapping correlations that the IVs have with one another.
To account for overlapping correlation, we must calculate either
partial or semipartial correlation to determine the unique correlation
between the IV and the DV (Field, 2005). Partial correlation (i.e., par-
tial r ) is the unique correlation between two variables, separate from the
other variables. Given three variables, X

Semipartial correlation is the unique correlation between two variables,
such that the in uence of a third variable has been removed from only
one of the other two variables. Given three variables, X

Assumptions and Other Model Requirements
Linear regression analysis is a parametric test that is used to make
inferences about a population. Thus, the four assumptions described
in Chapters 1 and 4DV measured at the interval or ratio-level data,
122 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
normally distributed data, homogeneity of variance, and independence of
observationsapply to this procedure. In addition, because linear regres-
sion analysis is a form of the general linear model, other assumptions and
model requirements are necessary, and are described as follows:
The relationship between the IVs and the DV is linear.
The idea here is that Y
i
is expected to increase by b
YX
units for every one
unit increase in X
i
, because the relationship between X
i
and Y
i
is assumed
to be linear. One common method for evaluating the linearity assump-
tion is to produce a scatterplot of the pairs of scores for the DV against
each IV and then examine the shape of the distribution to assess linearity.
The companion website of this book includes step-by-step instructions
for assessing the linearity assumption using a scatterplot. Another com-
mon method is to plot the standardized residuals against the standardized
predicted values (Lomax, 1992). In either case, if nonlinearity is present,
the overall shape of the distribution will be non-linear. Minor deviations
do not have a major impact on regression results. For serious violations,
the data can be transformed in a way that increases linearity. Field (2005)
provides a thorough discussion of transforming nonlinear data.
If the relationship is not linear, then the amount that Y
i
is expected
to increase depends on the particular value of X
i
(Lomax, 1992). Using
a variation of an example by Keith (2006, p. 170), consider the level of
anxiety in passing a standardized preliminary examination as the IV,
measured on a three-point scale (i.e., low, average, and high), and actual
performance on the prelim exam as the DV, measured as a ratio-level
variable on a scale from 0 to 100. Imagine that on average, students who
have little anxiety about the exam score low ( M = 20) and students who
have high anxiety also score low ( M = 20). Imagine further that students
who have an average amount of anxiety score much higher ( M = 80). If
we were to graph these means, we would observe that prelim test anxiety
has a curvilinear relationship with prelim test results such that test scores
vary based on level of anxiety, with low and high anxiety associated with
low scores and average anxiety associated with higher scores. The impli-
cations for analysis with curvilinear relationships are beyond the scope of
this book. If you confront this situation in your analysis, we suggest that
you consult Keith as he provides detailed instructions for dealing with
curvilinear relationships.
Bivariate and Multivariate Linear Regression Analysis 123
The errors are independent of (i.e., uncorrelated with) one
another. This is referred to as a lack of autocorrelation.
This assumption means that the distribution of the error values fol-
lows a random rather than systematic pattern. Violations of this assump-
tion occur when errors are positively or negatively correlated with one
another. Violations affect the accuracy of the standard error estimates,
which can increase the likelihood of making a Type I or Type II error.
Violations can be detected by examining the shape of the residual plot
(e.g., e
i
vs. X
i
) to determine the extent of randomness in the distribution,
or by examining the results of the DurbinWatson test. The Durbin
Watson test is available in SPSS and other statistical software programs.
Some research designs are more vulnerable to violations of the inde-
pendence of errors assumption than others. Longitudinal designs, designs
with data collected from multiple groups of people in different locations
(e.g., children in classrooms), and designs that involve replication are
more likely to result in violating the independence of errors assumption,
relative to other designs. On the other hand, this assumption is usually
met when participants are randomly assigned to groups or with designs
that include only one observation (Lomax, 1992).
The variance of the errors should be constant for all values
of X .
This is referred to as homogeneity of variance or homoscedasticity.
It means that the variances should be equal for all values of the IVs. A
violation of this assumption (i.e., unequal variances) is referred to as het-
eroscedasticity . Violations do not necessarily affect estimated regression
coef cients. However, violations may result in in ated standard errors,
and thus lead to an increased likelihood of making a Type II error (fail-
ing to reject a false null hypothesis and discarding an IV that is actually
signi cant).
SPSS offers three ways to determine whether the homogeneity of
variance assumption has been violated. First, one can produce a plot of
the standardized residuals against the standardized predicted values and
then examine the shape of the distribution. Data points that are evenly
dispersed indicate that the assumption of homoscedasticity has been
met. Another method is to examine the results of the Levene test for
124 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
homogeneity of variance. If the test statistic is nonsigni cant, then we
retain the null hypothesis that the difference between the variances equals
0, and the assumption has been met. A third method is to calculate and
examine the variance ratio. SPSS offers the Hartleys F
MAX
procedure as a
way to do this. Note that the Levenes test is affected by sample size such
that, in large samples, its results can be signi cant even when variances
are not different. We recommend examining the plot of the standardized
residuals and the Hartleys F
MAX
to con rm results of the Levenes test.
What can be done to correct for violations of this assumption? Minor
violations have a negligible impact on the results. To address serious vio-
lations, however, one can consider what is referred to as variance-stabi-
lizing transformations, such as taking the log or square root of Y (Lomax,
1992). Another option is to use a different method of estimation that
does not require homogeneity of variance, such as the weighted-least-
squares method.
The distribution of the residuals should approximate the shape
of a normal curve.
Errors are assumed to be normally distributed, roughly in the shape
of the normal curve. A nonnormal distribution of the residuals affects
the precision of the estimated coef cients. The risk of violating this
assumption is higher when observations include outliers, when samples
are small (< 25 per group), and when sample sizes across groups are not
equal (Lomax, 1992). Several graphing options are available to assess the
extent to which the shape of the distribution of errors is normal (e.g.,
histograms, stem and leaf plots, box plots, or Q-Q plots). In general, even
with moderate violations of the normality assumption, results are fairly
robust. In severe cases, one can apply techniques such as logarithmic
transformation to modify the shape of the distribution, or use tests that
do not require normal distributions of errors (i.e., nonparametric tests).
Other Model Requirements
The model should be correctly speci ed.
For a model to be correctly speci ed, several conditions must be
met. First, all relevant IVs must be included in the model. Second, all
Bivariate and Multivariate Linear Regression Analysis 125
irrelevant variables should be excluded from the model. Third, each IV
should be measured without error. Finally, the models IVs should not be
correlated with variables that are not in the model. If an IV is correlated
with a variable that has not been included in the model, the coef cient
estimate for the IV in our model may not accurately re ect the true rela-
tionship between the IV and the DV. In other words, this relationship
may be confounded by a third variable outside of the model.
The independent variables in the model should not be strongly
correlated with one another (i.e., no multicollinearity).
When IVs are strongly correlated with one another, this is referred to
as multicollinearity . IVs that are strongly correlated with one another
are basically measuring the same thing. Thus, the values of the estimated
coef cients for strongly correlated IVs would be interchangeable, making
it nearly impossible to determine their unique contribution to explaining
the variance in the DV.
Multicollinearity leads to increased chances of underestimating the
multiple correlation coef cient because the unique contribution of highly
correlated IVs is not being accounted for. As Field (2005) points out,
increased collinearity leads to increased standard errors of the estimated
coef cients, which increases the possibility of making a Type II error.
Multicollinearity can be assessed by examining the correlation matrix
for excessively high correlations between pairs of variables. Correlation
values greater than .80 ( r > .80) between two IVs may indicate multi-
collinearity (Abu-Bader, 2006, p. 102). Also, SPSS offers tests to conduct
collinearity diagnostics. One of the more common tests is the variance
in ation factor (VIF). A VIF value of 10 or greater suggests that mul-
ticollinearity between two IVs in the model is likely (Wetherill, 1986).
Multicollinearity can be addressed in at least one of two waysby
removing one of the IVs from the model that is causing the problem or
by combining the IVs to create a composite variable (Abu-Bader, 2006).
There should be no in uential outliers among the IVs or in the
solution.
One important requirement in linear regression analysis is the absence
of extreme cases, or cases with values that have an unusually large impact
126 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
on the results, relative to the other cases. These types of cases are referred
to as outliers . Outliers can affect the results in two ways. First, cases with
values that are smaller or larger than the other cases can in ate or de ate
correlation coef cients. In other words, outliers can bias the results because
they affect the value of the estimated coef cients. Second, outliers can also
affect the intercept and/or the slope of the regression line such that the
intercept may cross the Y -axis at a lower or higher point or the slope can
become steeper or atten. SPSS and other statistical software programs
offer several statistics that can be used to assess the impact of outliers on
the results. We will go over these statistics and the process of determining
the impact of outliers in the example at the end of the chapter.
Outliers that have extreme residual values can also affect regression
results. Any case with a large residual, relative to the other cases, may be
an outlier. At least two methods are available to identify residuals with
extreme values. Scatterplots of residuals provide a visual display that can
be used to identify cases with extreme residuals. We can also convert the
residuals into a standard unit of measurement to produce standardized
residuals, and then determine whether any have an absolute value greater
than 3. If so, this is indicative of a case that has an unusually large in u-
ence on the results (Tabachnick & Fidell, 1996).
The sample size should be large enough to detect results at the
desired effect size.
The minimum acceptable sample size (i.e., number of cases) for lin-
ear regression analysis depends on the size of the effect we hope to detect
(i.e., small, medium, or large), the alpha level selected for statistical sig-
ni cance (e.g., .05), and the level of power it will take to detect the effect.
A number of computer programs are available to calculate minimum
sample size based on desired effect size. Two examples are Sample Power,
which is available as part of SPSS Add On, and G*Power, which can be
downloaded from the Internet at no cost.
The IVs can be measured at any level of measurement (i.e.,
nominal, ordinal, interval, or ratio).
While IVs can be measured at any level of measurement in multiple
regression analysis, it is necessary to modify (i.e., recode) nominal or
Bivariate and Multivariate Linear Regression Analysis 127
ordinal-level IVs that have more than two values or categories (e.g., race),
prior to conducting the analysis. This is because linear regression proce-
dures can only handle interval or ratio-level IVs, and nominal or ordinal-
level IVs with two values only (i.e., dichotomous). Thus, if a nominal or
ordinal-level IV includes more than two values, it is necessary to recode
that variable into a series of categorical IVs with only two values each.
For example, we may have an IV that indicates a respondents marital
status with four categoriesmarried, unmarried, divorced, or widowed.
In order to measure whether a respondents particular marital status is
related to the DV, we must recode the marital status variable into four
new variables, each with two valuesmarried or not, unmarried or not,
divorced or not, and widowed or not. This recoding procedure is called
dummy coding. The companion website for this chapter provides an
example of dummy coding with step by step instructions for conducting
this procedure in SPSS.
An Additional IV Consideration: Interactions
Interaction effects occur when the impact of one IV on the DV depends
on the value of another IV. Thus, the impact on the DV is the combined
effect of the two IVs. Interaction effects can be examined in multiple lin-
ear regression analysis. To test for interaction effects of two IVs on the
DV in multiple regression models, it is necessary to create an IV that
represents the interaction effect. This is done by multiplying together
the two IVs in question. The results are then used to create the interac-
tion variable. Interactions between IVs measured at either the nominal
or interval/ratio-levels can be examined; this is one of the advantages of
multiple linear regression analysis compared to two-way ANOVA, which
can only test for interactions between nominal-level variables. A detailed
presentation of testing interactions in multiple regression analysis is
beyond the scope of this book. For more information on this topic, see
Keith (2006).
Methods of Data Entry in Multiple Linear Regression Analysis
Three methods of data entry are available in conducting multiple lin-
ear regression analysis simultaneous (i.e., forced entry or standard)
multiple regression , sequential (i.e., hierarchical) multiple regression ,
128 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
and statistical (i.e., stepwise) multiple regression . These methods are
differentiated from one another based on the way in which the IVs are
entered into the equation when running the model. What drives the deci-
sion to use one method over another is the extent to which theory or pre-
vious research leads us to expect that the IVs will be correlated with one
another. In other words, what is known about their shared or overlapping
variance in explaining the DV?
A very important point here is that the output differs depending on
which method is used. This is because of differences in the order of entry
of the IVs, and the fact that the order of entry provides different infor-
mation about the effects of the IVs on the DV. In simultaneous mul-
tiple regression, all IVs are entered into the equation at the same time.
Simultaneous multiple regression analysis provides information about
the direct effects of the IVs on the DV. This method is used when IVs are
expected to contribute fairly equally in explaining the DV and when they
are not expected to be highly correlated with one another.
In sequential or hierarchical multiple regression, IVs are entered into
the equation in a predetermined order in multiple steps, either individu-
ally or as groups. This order is determined based on existing knowledge
about the level of logical or theoretical importance of particular IVs in
predicting the DV, or based on time precedence (Keith, 2006). One focus
of sequential multiple regression analysis is the magnitude of the change
in R
2
from one step to the next. Sequential multiple regression analysis
provides information about the total effects of the IVs on the DV, includ-
ing indirect effects of IVs. The order of entry of the IVs is critical, as the
output may vary depending on the sequence in which IVs are entered in
the model. Regardless of the predetermined order of entry, you must be
able to defend and justify your decisions.
Finally, statistical multiple regression involves using a statistical pro-
cedure rather than theory to determine the order of entry for each IV. As
such, the computer selects the order of the IVs rather than on the basis of
theory or prior research. This method should be used with caution and
primarily for exploratory purposes.
Research Examples using Multiple Linear Regression Analysis
Linear regression analysis is an appropriate method to use as a
data-analytic procedure when the intent is to determine factors that
Bivariate and Multivariate Linear Regression Analysis 129
predict an outcome (the DV) measured at the interval or ratio-level.
Income is frequently measured at the ratio level and is appropriate as
a DV in multiple linear regression analysis. Linear regression analysis
is also often used in studies that use scales to measure outcomes, such
as the Child Behavior Checklist (CBCL), used to rate child problem
behaviors, or the Center for Epidemiologic Studies Depression Scale
(CES-D), which assesses depression. Shiovitz-Ezra and Leitsch (2010)
used the Revised UCLA Loneliness Scale (R-UCLA) (Russell, Peplau,
& Cutrona, 1980) to examine the relationship between perceived and
actual social ties (the IVs) and loneliness (the DV) among the elderly.
The DV was measured at the interval level. The authors found that the
number of friends and relatives, the frequency of their contact, and the
quality of the interactions were negatively related to loneliness among
older adults (i.e., as the values of the IVs increased, the value of the DV
decreased).
In another example, Nasim et al. (2009) used sequential linear regres-
sion analysis to identify risk and protective factors (the IVs) associated
with alcohol and tobacco refusal attitudes (the DVs) among 227 African-
American youth across individual, family, peer, and community domains.
The authors used the Speci c Events Drug and Alcohol Refusal Ef cacy
(SEDARE) scale (Connors, Plybon, & Pegg, 2003) to measure the DV.
The scale provides an assessment of refusal attitudes at the interval-level
of measurement. Sets of domain speci c IVs were entered into the equa-
tion in the following order: (a) individual, (b) peer, (c) family, and (d)
community, based on their expected level of importance in predicting
the DV. This allowed for an assessment of the relative effects of groups
of IVs within and across domains. As expected, ndings revealed differ-
ences between domains with regard to their relationship to tobacco- or
alcohol-refusal attitudes. Individual variables were more strongly related
to both alcohol- and tobacco-refusal attitudes, compared to variables in
the other domains.

Analysis of Variance
(ANOVA) and

INTRODUCTION
This chapter provides a description of Analysis of Variance (ANOVA)
and Analysis of Covariance (ANCOVA) methods of data analysis.
ANOVA and ANCOVA methods are used to compare means across dif-
ferent groups. Recall that the t test is also used to compare means between
groups. The t test, however, is used to compare means between no more
than two groups, whereas procedures from the ANOVA family can be
used to compare means between more than two groups. ANOVA pro-
cedures are often used in experimental research when the investigator is
interested in comparing outcomes across treatment and control groups.
For instance, Lindsey, Hayward, and DePan lis (2010) used ANOVA pro-
cedures to assess differences in outcomes between four groups of people
randomly assigned to one of the following conditions: (a) enhanced
intervention for three months, (b) enhanced intervention for nine
months, (c) regular intervention for three months, and (d) regular inter-
vention for nine months, in their evaluation of Family Connections, a
134 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
program designed to prevent behavioral problems among children at risk
of neglect.
As mentioned in the Introduction, while ANOVA and multiple
regression analysis share the assumption of linearity in the relation-
ship between X and Y , there are important differences between the two
methods (Keith, 2006). For instance, linear regression models include IVs
measured at any level whereas ANOVA models examine the impact of
IVs measured only at the nominal level. Also, analyses typically involve
assessing the impact of several IVs in multiple linear regression; the num-
ber of IVs in ANOVA is limited. Finally, ANOVA procedures are often
used in intervention research, where the goal is to determine the impact
of a treatment on an outcome. Linear regression analysis can be used for
this purpose, and it can also be used in nonexperimental research where
the intention is to simply describe relationships.
Types of ANOVA Procedures
The ANOVA family includes several types of statistical tests. Commonly
used tests are one-way ANOVA, two-way ANOVA, factorial ANOVA,
multivariate ANOVA (also referred to as MANOVA), ANCOVA, and
repeated measures ANOVA. These tests share two featuresthe DVs are
always measured on an interval or ratio-level and the IVs are always mea-
sured at the nominal level. The tests differ with regard to the number of
DVs and IVs in the model. The rst three tests (i.e., one-way ANOVA,
two-way ANOVA, and factorial ANOVA) are based on models with only
one DV; they differ in the number of IVs in the model. One-way ANOVA
is a bivariate test used to examine models with one DV and one IV. In
two-way ANOVA , the model includes one DV and two IVs. Factorial
ANOVA tests models with one DV and three or more IVs. MANOVA
tests are conducted on models with more than one DV and IV. ANCOVA
is another frequently used procedure from the ANOVA family. In addi-
tion to one DV and one IV, ANCOVA models include what is referred to
as covariates . Covariates are explanatory variables that are hypothesized
to explain some of the variance on the DV, beyond that of the IV. We will
explain covariates in more detail later in this chapter.
One-way ANOVA, two-way ANOVA, factorial ANOVA, multivari-
ate ANOVA, and ANCOVA also share the feature that all sample partici-
pants must be members of only one condition or level of the IV so that
Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) and Covariance (ANCOVA) 135
participant scores are independent (i.e., mutually exclusive) across levels.
The repeated-measures ANOVA procedure does not have this require-
ment. Participants can be assessed under more than one condition in
the experiment. Repeated-measures ANOVA is often used in longitudi-
nal studies that employ experimental or quasiexperimental designs with
multiple data collection follow-ups. For example, in their study to assess
the effectiveness of parent-child interaction therapy, Leung, Tsang, and
Heung (2009) used repeated measures ANOVA to analyze data collected
at three pointspretest, posttest, and six month follow-up. In this chap-
ter, we explain one-way and two-way ANOVA, and ANCOVA.
Structure of the Chapter
This chapter is divided into four sections. In the rst section we pro-
vide a detailed explanation of one-way ANOVA, including relevant basic
statistics that inform ANOVA models (i.e., mean and variance), the
ANOVA Source table (i.e., components of the actual analysis), estima-
tion procedures, model assumptions, and procedures for making mul-
tiple comparisons. We conclude this section by providing a description
of examples from social work research that have used one-way ANOVA
methods in analyzing data. In the second section, we explain two-way
ANOVA. This presentation begins with a general description and pur-
pose. Then we de ne important terms and describe model assumptions,
hypothesis testing, and partitioning sums of squares. Examples of social
work research using two-way ANOVA are provided at the end of this
section. The third section provides an overview of ANCOVA, includ-
ing key concepts, model requirements and assumptions, and social work
research examples using ANCOVA methods. In the nal section, we pro-
vide step-by-step instructions for conducting one-way ANOVA in SPSS,
with data from the National Educational Longitudinal Study of 1988
(NELS: 88).

and represents membership in one of multiple groups within which to
compare means on the outcome.
