What distinguishes one-way ANOVA from t tests with independent
samples? In other words, if the focus is on comparing means between
groups, why not just use the t test for independent samples for each pair
of groups? Abu-Bader (2006) identi es two reasons. First, in studies with
more than two groups, it would be necessary to conduct multiple t tests
in order to examine mean differences among all the possible pairs of
groups. For instance, perhaps you wish to conduct an experiment exam-
ining an intervention to increase healthy eating among children in low-
income families. Previous research suggests that your pretest measure
may have an effect on outcomes, independent of the intervention. Thus,
Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) and Covariance (ANCOVA) 137
you decide to test this intervention using a Solomon Four-Group design
so you can examine pretest effects. Your design looks like this:
Experiment 1 Treatment: R O
1
X O
2
Experiment 1 Control: R O
3
O
4
Experiment 2 Treatment: R X O
5
Experiment 2 Control: R O
6
If you used independent-samples t test to examine mean differences
between groups, you would have to conduct six separate tests to determine
differences in the means for all possible pairs (i.e., [a] Experiment 1 treat-
ment vs. Experiment 1 control, [b] Experiment 1 treatment vs. Experiment
2 treatment, [c] Experiment 1 treatment vs. Experiment 2 control, [d]
Experiment control 1 vs. Experiment 2 treatment, [e] Experiment 1 con-
trol vs. Experiment 2 control, and nally [f] Experiment 2 treatment vs.
Experiment 2 control). As you can see, this is labor intensive.
Building on this, the second reason for not using the
independent-samples t test when the mean of more than one pair of
groups is compared is because of the increased risk of making a Ty pe I
error (i.e., incorrectly rejecting the null hypothesis when it is true). The
alpha level for one t test is typically set at .05. For a set of t tests, the over-
all alpha level increases making it larger than the alpha level for only one
test. This is because the risk of making a Type I error grows or accumu-
lates across the multiple comparisons. Lomax (1992) provides a useful
analogy. He states, For each test we are taking a risk; the more tests we
do, the more risks we take. This can be explained by considering the risk
you take each day you drive your car to school or work. The risk of an
accident is small for any one given day. However, over a period of a year
the risk of experiencing an accident is much larger (p. 89).
What would the Type I error be if we used independent-samples t
tests to evaluate the differences in means among groups in our Solomon
Four-Group example? We would need to conduct six tests. We set an
alpha level of .05 for each test, indicating that the probability of falsely
rejecting the null hypothesis (Type I error) is 5%, and the probability of
not making a Type I error is 95% for each test. Because each test is inde-
pendent, we multiply their probabilities to determine the overall prob-
ability of not making a Type I error, which is .95
6
= .95 .95 .95 .95
.95 .95 = .74. Thus, the probability of making at least one Type I error
138 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
is .26 or 26% (1 .74), if we used independent-samples t -tests. So, in this
example, the probability of making a Type I error increased from 5% to
26%! The error rate across multiple tests in the same analysis is called the
family-wise (i.e., experiment-wise) Type I error rate .
In order to correct the in ated error rate in ANOVA, we use what is
referred to as an overall omnibus test to examine difference in means
across multiple groups. This involves conducting only one test that com-
pares mean differences between groups simultaneously. The F statistic can
be used for this purpose. In essence it is an extension of the independent
t test for two or more sample means that controls for the family-wise
error rate . We cover the F statistic in more detail in the next section.
Relevant Basic Statistics in ANOVA
Essentially, ANOVA is built on two basic statisticsthe mean and the vari-
ance. The variance is particularly important because it is used to determine
the sums of squares and the omnibus F test. First, however, we discuss the
mean. The purpose of using ANOVA in data analysis is to determine dif-
ferences in means between groups. Thus, the mean is also a very important
statistic. Recall that the mean is de ned as the arithmetic average of a set of
scores in a distribution. It is one of the three measures of central tendency
(i.e., mean, median, and mode) used to describe data. The mean is calcu-
lated by summing the values of all the scores in a distribution, and then
dividing the total by the number of cases in the study. For instance, if the
number of cases is 175, and the values of a set of scores sum to 2,051, then
the mean is 11.72 (2051 175). Because the focus is on group differences
across means, the DV in ANOVA models must always be measured at the
interval or ratio-level so that a legitimate mean can be determined.
The other important statistic is the variance . In ANOVA, estimates of
the variance are used to compare means between groups. The variance is
one of the three measures used to describe the dispersion, or variability,
of the data for a particular variable. Other dispersion measures are the
range and the standard deviation. The variance provides an estimate of
how spread out the distribution of scores is from the variables mean
(Abu-Bader, 2006). The value of the variance indicates the extent of that
spread. The more spread out the scores are from the mean, the larger
the value of the variance. The closer the scores cluster around the mean,
the smaller the value of the variance. The variance provides information
Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) and Covariance (ANCOVA) 139
about how well the estimated model actually ts the data. This is because
it measures the average error (i.e., spread) between the mean and the
scores (Field, 2005).
In ANOVA, the focus is on identifying where variance occurs between
and/or within groups, more formally referred to as between-groups
variance and within-groups variance . Remember that in ANOVA we
wish to determine mean differences between the groups in our study.
Between-groups variance indicates how the means vary from group to
group (e.g., treatment vs. control group) relative to the combined mean for
all groups. Within-group variance provides a measure of the variation in
mean scores for each participant in the same group (e.g., the mean scores of
participants in the treatment group), relative to the group mean. The total
variance is the sum of the between-group variation and the within-group
variation. In experimental research, we hope to nd more dispersion
between the treatment and control groups than within each group. This
would re ect differences between the groups and, depending on our
research design, might indicate the effectiveness of the intervention.

in Y . Recall that the total sum of squares is partitioned into two compo-
nentssum of squares predicted by the regression equation (SS

The variance has an important role in determining statistical signi -
cance of ANOVA models. Earlier we mentioned that the omnibus F test
(rather than multiple t tests) is used to determine statistical signi cance
in ANOVA. The F test allows us to test for mean differences between
groups simultaneously, decreasing the likelihood of incorrectly rejecting
the null hypothesis when it is true (i.e., Type I error). The F test produces
140 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
the F statistic, which is the ratio of the two estimated components of
the total variancethe between-groups estimated variance and the
within-groups estimated variance. The formula is: F = between-groups
estimate of variance within-groups estimate of variance. Because the F
statistic has an F sampling distribution, the F -Table is used to determine
statistical signi cance. If the F test is statistically signi cant, then the
null hypothesis that all population means are equal is rejected. This also
means that the alternative hypothesis (i.e., at least one population mean
is different from the other population means) is retained. Note that this
does not indicate which particular population mean differs from the
means of the other groups. To determine which group mean(s) differs
from the other group means, it is necessary to conduct planned or post
hoc-comparisons of means, also called contrasts. We cover contrasts
later in this chapter.
Lets get back to the F statistic, in particular how its numerator
(i.e., between-groups variation) and denominator (i.e., within-groups
variation) are estimated. The estimate of the numerator represents the
mean variance of the between-groups sum of squares . The estimate of the
denominator represents the mean variance of the within-groups sum of
squares . The between-groups mean square, denoted MS
betw
, is calculated
by dividing the sum of the variation between the groups (i.e., SS
betw
) by
its degrees of freedom. The degrees of freedom for the between-groups
sum of squares is calculated by subtracting 1 from the total number of
groups in the model. If k = the total number of groups in the model,
then the formula for the degrees of freedom between groups is k 1.
Similarly, the within-groups mean square, denoted MS
with
, is calculated
by dividing the sum of the variation within the groups (i.e., SS
with
) by its
degrees of freedom. The degrees of freedom for the within-groups sum
of squares is calculated by subtracting the total number of groups in the
model ( k ) from the total sample size ( n ), or n k . Thus, the formula for
the F statistic is MS
betw
MS
with
, where MS
betw
is the estimate of the mean
between-groups variance and MS
with
is the estimate of the mean within-
groups variance.
The ANOVA Summary Table
How the sources of variation are partitioned in one-way ANOVA is
often reported in a table referred to as the ANOVA Summary (i.e.,
Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) and Covariance (ANCOVA) 141
Source) Table . In fact, SPSS provides this table as a part of its output.
Table 6.1 provides the general form of the ANOVA summary table. The
rst column lists the two sources of variationbetween-groups and
within-groupsand the total variation. The second column provides
the sum of squares for each source. The third column indicates their
degrees of freedom. The mean squares reported in the fourth column
are the estimated average variances. The mean between-groups vari-
ance is determined by dividing the between-groups sum of squares by
its degrees of freedom (i.e., k 1). The mean within groups variance is
calculated by dividing the within-groups sum of squares by its degrees
of freedom (i.e., n k ). Finally, the F statistic is simply the ratio of the
between-groups mean sum of squares and the within-groups mean sum
of squares.

Similar to multiple regression analysis, ANOVA model parameters
are estimated using the least square estimator. In ANOVA, we also wish
to determine a set of estimates that minimizes the sum of the squared
residuals. The least squares estimator provides estimates such that the
sum of the squared residuals is smallest.

Assumptions and Other Model Requirements
As with multiple linear regression analysis, one-way ANOVA pro-
duces estimates of parameters that are intended to represent a popula-
tion. ANOVA is a parametric test and thus shares the four assumptions
described in Chapter 4DV measured at the interval or ratio-level data,
normally distributed data, homogeneity of variance, and independence
of observationsand the three assumptions about the distribution of
the residuals or errors (i.e.,
ij
)that they are normally distributed, inde-
pendent within and across groups, and with equal variance. We can sum-
marize this into one statementerrors are assumed to be independent
and normally distributed with equal variances. In the following section,
we review the three assumptions about the residuals and what to do if the
assumptions are violated.
First, errors are assumed to be independent within and across groups.
In other words, the scores of one participant should not in uence the
scores of another participant. The pattern of errors should be random
Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) and Covariance (ANCOVA) 143
rather than systematic. Systematic error might be indicated when the
errors in one group are large compared to the errors of the other groups,
suggesting a relationship between X and (Lomax, 1992). A violation of
this assumption may result in incorrect standard errors of the sample
means, which can increase the likelihood of making a Type I or Type II
error. Potential violations can be assessed by examining the residual plots
of the groups. No discernable pattern of data points should be observed.
The DurbinWatson test can also be used to evaluate violations of the
independence of error assumption. Time series designs, designs that
involve observations of groups (e.g., multiple classrooms of students),
and designs with repeated observations are particularly vulnerable to
violations of the independence assumption. On the other hand, this
assumption is usually met when participants are randomly assigned to
groups or with designs that include only one observation.
Second, errors are assumed to be normally distributed. Graphs such
as histograms, stem and leaf plots, or box plots can be used to determine
whether the distribution of the errors is shaped in a way that resembles a
normal curve. As mentioned in Chapter 5, results remain fairly robust in the
context of moderate violations of the normality assumption. Again, in severe
cases, you can consider using nonparametric tests that do not require a nor-
mal distribution of errors, or transforming the shape of the distribution.
The nal assumption is that the distributions of the residual errors
have equal variances across groups. This is referred to as homogeneity of
variance or homoscedasticity . A violation of the homogeneity assump-
tion may lead to an incorrect SS
with
(i.e., within-groups sum of squares)
which increases the likelihood of making Type I or Type II errors. As with
violations of the normality assumption, violations of the homogeneity of
variance assumption are less likely to occur with large samples and when
sample sizes across groups are equal. One way to evaluate whether this
assumption has been violated is to compare the variances of each group
they should be fairly close in size. By default, SPSS reports the Levene test
as an indicator of whether the homogeneity of variance assumption was
met. Other tests are the Cochrans C and the Hartley F
MAX
.
Multiple Contrasts
So far weve covered statistical techniques that focus on overall results (i.e.,
omnibus F test,
2
, adjusted
2
, and
2
). Researchers are also interested
144 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
in assessing which of the means between pairs of groups is signi cantly
different from one another. This is determined by conducting planned
or posthoc comparisons or contrasts (denoted in the population as ).
In this context, the terms contrasts and comparisons are often used
interchangeably. Lomax (1992) refers to a contrast as a weighted combi-
nation of the means (p. 127), that entails comparing the means between
two groups (e.g., group 1 mean vs. group 2 mean), referred to as a simple
contrast, or sets of groups (e.g., group 1 and group 2 means vs. group 3
mean), referred to as a complex contrast. Regardless of the total number
of groups, contrasts are always pairwise, or made between two compo-
nents or entities. The purpose of conducting contrasts is to test speci c
hypotheses about differences between group means.
Procedures for conducting contrasts in ANOVA are designed to coun-
teract the likelihood of making a Type I error (i.e., incorrectly rejecting a
true null hypothesis) in comparing multiple means across groups. These
methods minimize the impact of family-wise error rates. Thus, we can
conduct tests to compare means between groups in our study (as if con-
ducting several t tests) in a way that strengthens the likelihood that the
family-wise error rate does not rise above .05.
Two types of contrasts are availableplanned and post-hoc. Planned
contrasts are hypothesized a priori , based on theory or previous research.
Post-hoc contrasts are done after examining initial model results, often in
response to a signi cant omnibus F test. Note that most contrast proce-
dures require independent and normally distributed residuals with equal
variances. Some procedures require additional assumptions such as equal
sample sizes across groups. In the following section, we provide an over-
view of common planned and post-hoc contrast tests that are available in
SPSS. First, we explain in more detail the nature of these tests.
Planned Contrasts
Planned contrasts are conducted to test speci c hypotheses about
group-mean differences developed a priori . These hypotheses are derived
before data are analyzed, and are based on theory or previous research.
Thus, compared to post-hoc contrasts, planned contrasts tend to be more
speci c and focused. Usually, fewer planned contrasts are conducted. The
statistical signi cance of the overall F test is of little relevance in conduct-
ing planned contrasts.
Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) and Covariance (ANCOVA) 145
Recall that, in ANOVA, the total variance is split into two parts
between-groups variance and within-groups variance. In the context
of an experimental design, between-groups variance represents varia-
tion due to the experiment (SS
betw
or SS
M
), whereas within-group vari-
ance represents variation due to error, or unexplained variance (SS
with
or SS
R
). The focus of planned contrasts is to examine variation due to
the experimental manipulation (SS
betw
). The variance attributed to the
experiment, SS
betw
, is partitioned into components. We then examine
contrasts between these components. For instance, say our experiment
involved three groupsa group that got the intervention (i.e., treat-
ment group), a group that got services as usual (i.e., alternative treat-
ment group), and a group that got no services (i.e., control group).
Two sets of contrasts would be tested to determine how the variance
explained by the experiment (i.e., between-groups variance) was par-
tialled out. In the rst contrast, we might compare mean differences
between the groups that got services (i.e., intervention group and ser-
vices as usual group) and the group that got no service. The second
contrast would then involve examining mean differences between the
services groupsthe intervention group and the services as usual
group. As adapted from Field (2005, p. 326), Figure 6.1 illustrates
this.
Three rules guide the process of conducting planned contrasts.
First, each contrast must include only two components. It may be that
one or more of the components include multiple groups, as in the pre-
vious example. The second rule is that component parts (i.e., groups in
the study) are mutually exclusive and independent of one another. In
other words, a group is only included once in a contrast. Third, the total
number of contrasts tested is always one less than the total number of
groups in the study. The previous example includes three groups (i.e.,
treatment group, services as usual group, and control group) and two
contrasts.
Contrasts must be de ned prior to running the tests. This is done
by assigning values to the coef cients of the equations that represent the
contrasts. These values are referred to as weights . Procedures for assign-
ing weights depend on whether a set of contrasts is orthogonal or non-
orthogonal . The following section describes what is meant by orthogonal
and nonorthogonal contrasts, and provides rules for assigning weights to
contrasts.
146 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
Orthogonal Contrasts
A set of contrasts is orthogonal if the component variances are indepen-
dent of one another. Orthogonality is based on the sum of the values
of contrast weights, multiplied together. If the products of the weights
in a set of contrasts sum to zero, then these contrasts are considered
orthogonal, and thus independent. Orthogonal contrasts require that
sample sizes across groups are equal. We will discuss how to conduct
contrasts in cases where group sample sizes are not equal later in the
chapter.
Table 6.2 provides an example of a set of orthogonal contrasts with
weights. The example is based on three groups with three means (i.e.,

differ from one another. For example, the values of the weights for the

contrast is 0 because the mean of the third group is not being evaluated
at this point. To determine whether this set of contrasts is orthogonal,
we multiply the values of the weights down each of the second, third,
and fourth columns and then add them together. If they sum to zero,
then the set of contrasts is orthogonal. As you can see, the column totals
[i.e., + ( ) + 0] sum to zero, which means this set of contrasts is
orthogonal.
To summarize, Field (2005) identi es the following rules to assign
values to weights.
Rule 1: Each contrast includes only two components of variation.
Rule 2: In the rst comparison, combine all experimental groups
(e.g., treatment and services as usual groups) to compare them
with control group(s).
Rule 3: If a group is singled out in one comparison, that group is
then excluded from subsequent contrasts.
Rule 4: Assign positive values of weights to one component of the
contrast and negative values of weights to the other component.
Rule 5: If a group is not included in the comparison, assign it a
weight of zero.
Rule 6: The sum of weights for a comparison equals zero. (p. 330)
SPSS offers the Planned Orthogonal Contrast (POC) procedure to
conduct a test of orthogonal contrasts. This test is used when contrasts
have been de ned a priori (i.e., planned rather than post-hoc) and the
set of contrasts is orthogonal (i.e., mutually exclusive). Note that sample
sizes for each group must be equal when using the POC procedure. If not,
then you can use the TukeyKramer test for unequal sample sizes, which
is discussed later in the chapter.

Nonorthogonal Contrasts
It is also possible to conduct tests of a set of nonorthogonal contrasts.
Nonorthogonal contrasts include components that are not mutually
exclusive. The sources of variation overlap or are not independent of one
another. Nonorthogonal contrasts differ from orthogonal contrasts in
that they do not represent nonredundant and independent sources of
variation. In this case, it is necessary to use a more conservative probabil-
ity level to determine the statistical signi cance of a particular contrast.
The Bonferroni Correction (discussed later) can be used to correct for
the overlap. Also, interpreting the results of nonorthogonal contrasts is
not as straightforward, relative to orthogonal contrasts.
Table 6.3 provides a set of nonorthogonal contrasts, based on a simple
modi cation of Table 6.2. As you can see, the example still includes three
groups, each with its own mean (i.e.,

of only two groups, 1 and 3, are compared, instead of comparing means
of all three groups as we did in the previous example. Thus, the values of
the weights as well as their products are different. As you can also see, the
products sum to 1 (1 + 0 + 0) rather than 0, which indicates that this set
of contrasts is not orthogonal.
Post-Hoc Contrasts
Post-hoc contrasts are similar to planned contrasts in that the intent is to
compare means of different combinations of groups in the study. There
are some critical differences however. Post-hoc contrasts are conducted
when no speci c hypotheses have been posited a priori . The statistical
signi cance (or not) of the overall F test informs the decision to conduct

post-hoc contrasts. They should only be conducted when the overall F
test is statistically signi cant (Howell, 2010). In post-hoc contrasts, all
possible pairs of means are tested. Because of this, the possibility of an
in ated Type I error rate increases. The tests for conducting post-hoc
contrasts correct for this by adjusting the Type I error critical value ( ).
These adjustments are intended to control the family-wise error rate.
Different types of adjustments are made depending on the speci c test.
Similar to planned comparisons, most post-hoc tests require indepen-
dent and normally distributed errors with equal variances.
A number of tests are available to conduct post-hoc contrasts, each
with different ways of controlling the family-wise error rate. Four post-
hoc tests that are frequently conducted when equality of variances is
assumed include Fishers LSD (least signi cant difference), Bonferroni
(also known as the Bonferroni correction), Scheffe, and Tukeys Honestly
Signi cant Difference (HSD) test. These tests require equal sample sizes
across groups. When sample sizes differ between groups, one can use the
Tukey Kramer test. When the homogeneity of variance assumption is not
met, the Tamabanes T2 can be used. Finally, the Kruskal-Wallis test is a
non-parametric test that can be used when the normality assumption is
violated. For a comprehensive presentation of these tests (and others) see
Lomax (2007).
Examples of Social Work Research using One-Way ANOVA
ANOVA procedures are used to examine questions about differences
in means between groups. Thus, ANOVA procedures are common in
experimental research where the focus is on determining the effects of an
intervention by comparing outcomes of treatment and control groups.
For instance, Edmond, Rubin, and Wambach (1999) used ANOVA proce-
dures to assess the impact of eye movement desensitization and reprocess-
ing (EMDR) in reducing trauma among adult females who experienced
childhood sexual abuse. Fifty-nine participants were randomly assigned
to three groupsEMDR treatment ( n = 20), routine treatment ( n = 20),
and control ( n = 19). Mean differences between groups on several out-
come measures were compared. Outcomes (i.e., the DVs) were measured
on an interval scale. The IV (i.e., assignment into the intervention group,
routine treatment group, or control group) was measured on a nominal
scale with three categories.
150 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
ANOVA procedures can also be used to analyze data from studies that
use quasiexperimental designs. Painter (2009) used a pre- and posttest
quasiexperimental design to compare multisystemic therapy (MST) to
the services-as-usual family skills training among a group of emotion-
ally disturbed children. Data were collected retrospectively from a com-
munity mental health services computerized data base of clients who had
completed MST ( n = 87) or services as usual ( n = 87). One-way ANOVA
was used to compare mean differences on improved functioning, using
responses to the Ohio Problem Severity scale (Ogles, Lunnen, Gillespie, &
Trout, 1996) and the Ohio Youth Functioning scale (Ogles et al.). Results
showed that youth who completed MST scored higher on outcomes, rela-
tive to the services-as-usual group. In this example, the DVs (the Ohio
Problem Severity scale and the Ohio Youth Functioning scale) were mea-
sured on an interval scale. The IV had two categories (MST group and
services-as-usual group) and was measured on a nominal scale.
TWO-WAY ANALYSIS OF VARIANCE (ANOVA): A DETAILED DESCRIPTION
In one-way ANOVA models, cases are separated into groups based on
one factor such as race/ethnicity, or in the case of experimental designs,
one of the studys conditions (e.g., treatment, services-as-usual, or con-
trol). This allows us to compare means of multiple groups across one fac-
tor. It is often the case that we are interested in comparing means across
more than one factor (e.g., study conditions AND race/ethnicity). In
other words, we wish to examine the impact of multiple IVs on the DV.
Two-way ANOVA allows us to do just that for designs with two factors
(i.e., IVs). At the beginning of the chapter, we described a study con-
ducted by Lindsey and others (2010) to evaluate the Family Connections
program. The authors used ANOVA procedures to assess differences in
outcomes between groups randomly assigned to one of four study condi-
tions. The factor or IV in this case was study condition. Suppose they
were also interested in differences across the four study conditions based
on family structure (e.g., two-parent families or single-parent families),
thus introducing a second IV, family structure, with cases separated into
two groupstwo-parent and single-parent families. The researchers
could use two-way ANOVA to determine mean differences across both
study conditions and family structure.
Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) and Covariance (ANCOVA) 151
Much of what was presented on one-way ANOVA is applicable in
two-way ANOVA models. There are some differences, however, which
are described in the following section and organized as follows. First, we
de ne two important conceptsmain effects and interaction effects
upon which two-way ANOVA models are based. Next, we present the
components of the two-way ANOVA population model, explain estima-
tion procedures, and describe how two-way ANOVA sums of squares dif-
fer from one-way ANOVA. We then describe the way in which two-way
ANOVA assumptions differ from the assumptions of one-way ANOVA.
We build on the discussion of multiple comparisons in one-way ANOVA
to provide a brief overview of how this is done in two-way ANOVA.
Finally, we provide examples of social work research that have used
two-way ANOVA as the data analysis method.
Important Concepts
Two-way ANOVA procedures involve comparing means between multi-
ple groups on two factors for both main effects and interaction effects. A
main effect is the direct or unique impact of a factor (i.e., IV) on the DV.
We test for main effects in one-way ANOVA by determining mean differ-
ences between groups. In the case of two-way ANOVA, we determine the
main effects of two factors, A and B, separately on the DV. In other words,
we determine the unique effect of factor A on the DV, controlling statisti-
cally for factor B, and the unique effect of B on the DV, controlling for
A. Building on our previous example of the Family Connections evalua-
tion (Lindsey et al., 2010), factor A would include the four study condi-
tions (i.e., 3-month regular, 9-month regular, 3-month enhanced, and
9-month enhanced). Factor B would be family structure (i.e., two-parent
and single-parent families). We evaluate study conditions and fam-
ily structure for their main effect, independent of the other factor. The
evaluation of each factor on the group means (the DV) produces an F
statistic as an indicator of whether the group means are equal.
An interaction effect represents the combined effect of the two fac-
tors on the group means. The purpose of testing for an interaction effect
is to determine whether the two factors operate independent of one
another (no interaction exists) or whether the two factors work together
to produce an additional impact, beyond the impact of their main effects.
In our example, we would examine whether study conditions and family
152 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
structure combine to have an impact on the outcomes, in addition to
their main effects. For instance, it may be that a longer intervention is
more successful for single-parent families that may not have as many
resources as two-parent families. We could determine this by testing the
interaction effect of study condition and family structure on group mean
outcomes. As with main effects, an F statistic is produced as an indica-
tor of statistical signi cance of the interaction. There are many ways
in which factors can combine with one another to produce interaction
effects. Lomax (1992, pp. 168170) provides a detailed description for
those who would like additional information.

Recall that the equation of the one-way ANOVA model is: Y

to the corresponding levels of each factor. The column means for each
factor level, referred to as marginal means, are provided at the bot-
tom of the respective column. At the end of each row are the marginal
means for each level of the factor displayed in that row. The value in
the lower right corner is the overall mean. Each cell provides the mean
of all the scores within the cell. The subscript numbers and dots after
each cell and marginal mean represent their location in the table. The
rst number or dot is always associated with the row location and the
second number or dot is always associated with the column location.
For example, the mean score for all two-parent families in the 3-month
enhanced treatment condition would be re ected in the rst cell of the
table, mean of Y

.

The way in which the sums of squares are partitioned in two-way ANOVA

Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) and Covariance (ANCOVA) 155
Assumptions
Similar to one-way ANOVA, in two-way ANOVA we assume that
errors are independent and normally distributed with a common vari-
ance. In this case, however, the focus is on the residuals within each
cell. These residuals re ect the difference between the values of each
observation and the cell mean. To determine error for each i
th
case, we
subtract its score from the cell mean. The difference represents error.
The consequences of violating assumptions in two-way ANOVA are
similar to the consequences for violating the assumptions in one-way
ANOVA. The same techniques can be used to detect assumption viola-
tions. However, the residual plots of cells rather than of the groups are
examined.
Multiple Comparisons in Two-Way ANOVA
In two-way ANOVA, contrasts of both main effects and interaction
effects are conducted. Much of what was presented in the previous
section on conducting multiple contrasts for one-way ANOVA can be
applied to conducting contrasts in two-way ANOVA. What is different
here is that in two-way ANOVA models, we are interested in examining
contrasts of both main and interaction effects. Thus, two-way ANOVA
models include more possible means to compare (i.e., cell and mar-
ginal means as shown in Table 6.4). It is important to clearly indicate
which means are being compared. As sample sizes within each cell and
for each marginal mean are likely to vary, it is also important to clearly
indicate the sample size for the particular means being compared. The
process for conducting contrasts in two-way ANOVA models is beyond
the scope of this book. If you are interested in this topic, see Field (2005)
or Lomax (1992).
Examples of Social Work Research using Two-Way ANOVA
Two-way ANOVA procedures are used when researchers wish to com-
pare means across two factors. In other words, we examine the impact of
two IVs, measured categorically, on one DV, measured at the interval or
ratio-level. In their randomized control trial, Silver and Bauman (2006)
compared differences in HIV/AID knowledge and sexual attitudes, inten-
tions, and peer norms between two groups of inner city youth. Two-way
156 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
ANOVA procedures were used to examine mean differences in three out-
comes (i.e., HIV/AID knowledge, abstinence self-ef cacy, and outcome
expectancies) based on sexual experience and gender. Thus, in this study
the two factors or categorical IVs were sexual experience and gender,
each with two levelssexual experience or sexual inexperience, and male
or female, respectively. The outcomes (i.e., DVs) were measured at the
ratio-level.
Nakonezny, Rodgers, and Nussbaum (2003) employed a quasi-
experimental pre- and posttest design with two-way ANOVA methods to
examine the impact of later-life parental divorce on relationships between
adult children and their parents. This study provides an example of the
use of two-way ANOVA procedures in nonintervention research. The
sample was divided into divorced families and intact families, and then
further divided into another two groups based on predivorce solidarity
in the adultchild/older parent relationship. Thus, the two factors are 1)
older-parent divorce status with two levels (divorced versus intact) and
2) predivorce solidarity in the adultchild/older parent relationship, also
with two levels (high pretest solidarity or low pretest solidarity). Three
types of relationship solidarity outcomes were examinedassociational
solidarity, affectional solidarity, and functional solidarityall measured
at the ratio-level.
ONE-WAY ANALYSIS OF COVARIANCE (ANCOVA): A DETAILED DESCRIPTION
We can build on what we learned about one-way ANOVA to understand
ANCOVA procedures. Essentially these procedures are similar, with one
major difference. Recall that the purpose of one-way ANOVA analysis is
to compare differences in means across groups. Thus, the DV is measured
at the interval or ratio-level (so we can calculate a legitimate mean) and
the factor or IV (the group variable) is categorical. These ideas extend
to ANCOVA models as well. However, ANCOVA allows us to examine
mean differences between groups, controlling for another variable that
may explain some of the reasons for the mean differences between the
groups. This is done by adding what is referred to as a covariate to the
model and testing its impact. Covariates are not DVs or IVs. They are
simply variables that are hypothesized to in uence mean differences
between groups in addition to the IV. By adding the covariate, we expect
Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) and Covariance (ANCOVA) 157
to explain more variation in the outcome, relative to one-way ANOVA.
ANCOVA calculates mean differences between groups, adjusted for the
impact of the covariate. Covariates are usually measured at the interval
or ratio-level.
Lets use the Lindsey et al. (2010) study to consider an example. Recall
that the purpose of this study was to test the impact of Family Connections
on child outcomes. The DV was based on responses to the Child Behavior
Checklist (CBCL) and the IV was group assignment to one of the four
study conditions. Suppose that, in the authors review of previous research,
they discovered that family-based interventions are more successful for
younger children. If this is the case, Lindsey and others might include in
their model a variable that measures child age, to control or account for
differences in intervention outcomes based on childrens ages.

The Mean and the Variance in ANCOVA
Lets discuss the mean and the variance in the context of ANCOVA. As
such we will review three relevant concepts covariate as a source of
variation in the model, adjusted means , and partitioning the variance
158 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
as represented through sums of squares. A covariate represents a source of
variation that has not been included in the experiment, but the evidence
(i.e., previous research or theory) suggests that it is likely to affect the DV.
Including a meaningful covariate in the model will hopefully increase the
amount of total variance that is explained. Lomax (1992) identi es four
reasons for including a covariate in an ANCOVA model(1) to reduce
within-group error variance, (2) to account for any preexisting mean
group differences based on the covariate, (3) to account for the relation-
ship between the covariate and the DV, and (4) to obtain a more precise
and less biased estimate of the effect of the IV on the DV (p. 281).
The group means are adjusted as a consequence of including a cova-
riate in the model. That is, by including the covariate in the analysis, we
statistically remove or control for the effects of its variation on the group
means of the DV, referred to as adjusted means. In the context of experi-
mental research, the need to adjust group means may occur when one
is unable to use random assignment to form the intervention and con-
trol groups. Without the use of random assignment, preexisting group
differences are likely to be present, and thus confound the relationship
between the treatment and the outcome. These preexisting group differ-
ences can be represented in the statistical models as confounding vari-
ables, or covariates, so their in uence can be accounted for.
We can understand how the total variance is partitioned in an
ANCOVA model by examining the sums of squares. There are three
sources of variation in a one-way ANCOVA modelbetween-groups
adjusted, within-groups adjusted, and the covariate. Note that the between
groups and within groups variation have been adjusted to account for the
covariate. The equation is: SS
total
= SS
betw(adj)
+ SS
with(adj)
+ SS
cov
.
ANCOVA Assumptions and Conditions
The assumptions about the residuals in one-way ANOVA models
independence, normal distribution, and common varianceare also
assumed for the ANCOVA residuals. ANCOVA includes four additional
assumptions related to the covariate, as follows:
Covariates are measured without error. In other words they are
perfectly reliable.
Analysis of Variance (ANOVA) and Covariance (ANCOVA) 159
There is a linear relationship between the covariate and the DV.
This is the same assumption we made about the relationship
between X and Y in linear regression.
The covariate relates to the DV in exactly the same way for
all groups in the model. This assumption is referred to as
homogeneity of regression . What it means is that the slopes of
the regression lines for each group are equal and the lines are
parallel to one another.
There is no relationship between the covariate and the treatment.
In other words, the IV and the covariate are independent of
one another. For instance, if group assignment to treatment
and control groups was based on age, then age would be an
inappropriate covariate because it is likely to be related to the
treatment.
SPSS provides several methods for determining whether these assump-
tions are met. Field (2005) provides a detailed explanation of these
methods.
Research Examples Using ANCOVA
Several social work researchers have used ANCOVA as their data-analysis
method. Arnold, Smith, Harrison, and Springer (1999) used ANCOVA
procedures in their evaluation of the Education Now and Babies Later
program. The purpose of this program was to prevent teen pregnancy
through abstinence. The evaluation sought to determine whether ado-
lescents who completed the pregnancy-prevention curriculum achieved
higher scores on an instrument that measured participant changes in
knowledge, beliefs, and attitudes about sexuality. The DV was partici-
pant posttest scores, the factor (or IV) was receipt of the intervention or
not, and the covariate was participant pre-test scores on the instrument.
The use of ANCOVA allowed the researchers to determine mean differ-
ences between the treatment and comparison groups, holding constant
participant knowledge, beliefs, and attitudes about sexuality prior to the
intervention. In other words, the posttest means re ected an adjustment
of the impact of the pretest means. Note that with this type of design (i.e.,
quasiexperimental) the independence of observations assumption does
160 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
not applydata were collected from each sample at two time points (i.e.,
pre- and posttest).
In another example, Auslander and others (2000) used ANCOVA
procedures to assess the impact of an intervention designed to reduce
the risk of diabetes among low-income African American women. In this
case, several outcomes (DVs) related to knowledge, attitudes, and behav-
iors of healthy eating were assessed. The factor or IV was participation
in the intervention or not and the covariate was, once again, the pre-test
scores. Mean differences between the treatment and control groups were
calculated on all outcome measures, controlling for pretest scores on the
measures.
CONDUCTING ONE-WAY ANOVA IN SPSS: AN EXAMPLE
To summarize, one-way ANOVA is used to examine mean differences
between two or more groups. It is a bivariate test with one IV and one
DV, with the IV measured at the nominal level and the DV measured
at the interval or ratio-level. The following provides instructions for
conducting one-way ANOVA, and planned and post-hoc comparisons.
The instructions also include a check for whether the homogeneity of
variance assumption has been met. A more detailed set of instructions is
available on the companion website of this book.
The DV is a measure of base year standardized reading scores
(BY2XRSTD); the IV is an indicator of the geographic region of each
school (G8REGON). The IV has four valuesnortheast (coded as 1),
north central (coded as 2), south (coded as 3), and west (coded as 4). This
analysis is based on 300 randomly selected cases with no missing obser-
vations from the NELS database. Although not used in this particular
analysis, the data set also includes one weight variable (F2PNWLWT).

Path Analysis
INTRODUCTION
Path analysis is a set of statistical procedures used to examine lin-
ear, causal relationships between variables. It is de ned as, a statistical
method for analyzing quantitative data that yields empirical estimates
of the effects of variables in a hypothesized causal system (Bohrnstedt &
Knoke, 1994, p. 414). It shares many features of multiple linear regres-
sion analysis (e.g., linearity in causal relationships). Path modeling is an
extension of multiple regression analysis in that it allows us to more fully
determine how IVs are related to the DV in a model. To understand what
we mean here, we return to our discussion on methods of data entry
(i.e., simultaneous, sequential, and statistical) in multiple regression in
Chapter 5. Recall that the results of simultaneous multiple regression
analysis provide information about the direct effects of the IVs on the
DV whereas the results of sequential multiple regression analysis provide
information about the total effects of the IVs on the DV. In path analysis,
we can investigate direct effects, total effects, and indirect effects, which
can lead to stronger claims about the causal relationship between the vari-
ables. As we discussed in the Introduction, four conditions must be met
in order to establish a causal relationship between two variablesasso-
ciation, temporal ordering (i.e., time precedence), correct effect priority,
164 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
and nonspuriousness (i.e., no other plausible explanations of the rela-
tionship between the presumed cause and the presumed effect) (Kline,
2011). Path analytic techniques build on multiple regression analysis to
lend more explicit support for a causal relationship between variables,
particularly with regard to time precedence and nonspuriousness.
Path analysis is part of the structural equation modeling family. While
structural equation modeling (SEM) combines measurement and struc-
tural models to analyze both latent and observed variables, path analysis
focuses strictly on structural models with observed variables. However,
the basic principles of path analysis provide the foundation for analyz-
ing more complicated models in the SEM family, including measurement
models and those with latent variables.
Structure of the Chapter
The rst part of this chapter provides a detailed explanation of path
analysis, including correlation; path diagrams, equations, and coef -
cients; path decompositions; assumptions; model identi cation; and
model estimation. We refer to a study by Stewart (2006) described in
the following paragraph, as a means of illustration. This section con-
cludes with a description of examples from social work research that
have used path analytic methods. We then provide an overview of
structural equation modeling. At the end of the chapter, instructions
for conducting path analysis in AMOS (SPSS Inc., 2011) are provided,
using data from the National Educational Longitudinal Study of 1988
(NELS: 88).
Description of the Illustration
A study by Stewart (2006) is used to introduce and illustrate the prin-
ciples and concepts of path analysis throughout the chapter. The data
used for this study come from NELS: 88 data. Stewart (2006) examined
the in uence of individual and family factors on academic achievement
among African American youth. Figure 7.1 provides a path diagram of
her model. Stewart hypothesized that, among other factors, caregiver
involvement in youths schools and academic achievement in the eighth
grade would have a direct effect on achievement in 12th grade. She also
hypothesized that these factors would have indirect effects on 12th grade
Path Analysis 165
achievement through the youths involvement in extracurricular activi-
ties during the 10th grade. Finally, caregiver school involvement in the
eighth is also hypothesized to positively in uence 12th grade achieve-
ment indirectly through student motivation in the 10th grade. Thus,
Stewart posits that extracurricular activity involvement is both a cause
of 12th grade achievement and an effect of caregiverschool involvement
and academic achievement in the eighth grade. She also posits that stu-
dent motivation in the 10th grade is both a cause of 12th grade achieve-
ment and an effect of caregiver involvement in the eighth grade.
The signs near each path indicate the hypothesized direction of the
proposed relationships. In this case, all relationships are expected to be
positive. That is, increased caregiver involvement and academic achieve-
ment during the eighth grade, and extracurricular involvement and stu-
dent motivation in the 10th grade will lead directly to higher 12th grade
achievement. Moreover, increased caregiver involvement and achieve-
ment during the eighth grade is hypothesized to lead to extracurricular
involvement in the 10th grade, which will then lead to higher achievement
in the 12th grade. Finally, increased caregiver involvement is expected to
result in increased student motivation in the 10th grade, which will then
also lead to higher achievement in the 12th grade.

PATH ANALYSIS: A DETAILED DESCRIPTION
Correlation as a Basic Statistic in Path Analysis
As with multiple linear regression analysis, correlation plays a major role
in path analysis. In both techniques, we estimate the correlation between
a set of IVs and a DV, measured on an interval or ratio scale, while con-
trolling for other IVs. However, in path analysis we build on the process
of controlling for other IVs by decomposing the correlation between
each IV and DV into its component partsdirect effect, indirect effect,
and/or spurious correlation.
Lets examine direct effects, indirect effects, and spurious correlations in
more detail. A direct effect is represented as a path between two variables,
without an intervening variable. Figure 7.1 provides several examples of
direct effects. For instance, the path from T1 Caregiver School Involvement
to T2 Student Motivation represents a proposed direct effect. An indirect
effect is represented as a path between two variables, with an intervening
variable between the other two variables. In Figure 7.1, the path from T1
Caregiver School Involvement to T2 Student Motivation to T3 12th Grade
Achievement represents a proposed indirect effect of T2 Student Motivation
(the intervening variable) in predicting the impact of T1 Caregiver School
Involvement on T3 12th Grade Achievement. A spurious correlation occurs
when the relationship between an IV and a DV is caused by another IV.
For example, if the relationship between T1 Caregiver School Involvement
and T2 Student Motivation is actually caused by Parental Educational
Aspirations, then the correlation between T1 Caregiver School Involvement
Path Analysis 167
and T2 Student Motivation would be spurious. When a spurious correla-
tion exists, then we have not met the condition of non-spuriousness as a
part of the requirements for establishing causality.
De nitions of Other Important Terms
In previous chapters we introduced many terms that are used in linear
regression analysis and ANOVA. Some of these terms are also used in
path analysis. However, other terms that we have not encountered yet
are associated with path analysis. We have already introduced you to ve
termspath analysis, nonspuriousness, direct effects, indirect effects,
and spurious correlation. In this section we de ne 10 additional terms
and use Figure 7.1 to provide examples. All terms are de ned in the con-
text of presumed causality in path analysis. Five of the terms are variables
de ned from a causality framework; the other ve terms are components
of path analysis.
Thus far, we used the term independent variable to represent fac-
tors that are hypothesized to be associated with an outcome, and the term
dependent variable to represent the outcome. These terms are not typi-
cally used in path analysis. Instead, we use the term exogenous variable to
refer to a variable that we hypothesize to predict an outcome. Exogenous
variables are predetermined and, from a temporal-ordering perspective,
occur before the outcome. The symbol X is used to represent an exoge-
nous variable. Figure 7.1 includes two exogenous variablesT1 Caregiver
School Involvement and T1 8th Grade Achievement. The outcome of inter-
est, or what we intend to predict, is referred to as an endogenous variable .
The symbol, Y is typically used to denote an endogenous variable. Three
endogenous variables are included in Figure 7.1T2 Student Motivation,
T2 Extracurricular Involvement, and T3 12th Grade Achievement.
Relative to multiple regression analysis, one difference is that path
analysis usually involves models with more than one outcome of inter-
est. Another difference is that some endogenous variables can have dual
roles such that they can be modeled as both predictors and outcomes. In
Figure 7.1, T2 Student Motivation and T2 Extracurricular Involvement
are examples of endogenous variables with dual roles. These types of
variables are referred to as intervening variables . As Figure 7.1 shows,
T2 Student Motivation and T2 Extracurricular Involvement inter-
vene between the two exogenous variables (i.e., T1 Caregiver School
168 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
Involvement and T1 8th Grade Achievement) and the nal endogenous
variable, T3 12th Grade Achievement. Intervening variables are also
called mediating variables.
The fth variable term is residual variable. In path analysis, resid-
ual variables are similar to residual or error in linear regression analysis
in that they represent the unexplained portion of the XY path (i.e.,
1 R
2
). Sometimes residual variables are referred to as disturbances or
disturbance terms (e.g., Kline, 2011). As illustrated in Figure 7.1, each
endogenous variable (i.e., T2 Student Motivation, T2 Extracurricular
Involvement, and T3 12th Grade Achievement) has an associated residual
variable (i.e., R 1, R 2, and R 3). A residual variable represents other causes
of the associated endogenous variable that are not included in the model.
For example, the residual variable R 2 represents all causes of T2 Student
Motivation, in addition to T1 Caregiver Involvement. It is the explicit
focus on cause that differentiates residuals in path analysis from residuals
in linear regression analysis.
The other ve terms represent components of path analysis. A path
model is a causal representation of relationships among variables. A path
model is recursive (versus nonrecursive), which means that all causal rela-
tionships are assumed to occur in one direction (represented with arrows
pointing in one directionleft to right). Nonrecursive path models hypoth-
esize reciprocal relationships between variables (with arrows going in both
directions). A path model can be depicted using symbols in the form of an
equation or as a diagram. A path diagram is a pictorial or visual display of
cause and effect relationships among variables. A path coef cient, denoted
as P , is the numerical estimate of the causal relationship between two vari-
ables. The path coef cient represents the amount of expected change in
the variable representing the effect due to a one unit change in the vari-
able representing the cause. Path decompositions involve determining and
separating out the types of correlation between two variables. This might
include direct effects, indirect effects, and/or spurious correlations. In the
following section, we use these terms to explain the path model.
Components of a Path Model
Path Diagrams
A path diagram provides a picture of the path model. It is the graphic
equivalent to describing the model with a set of equations, which we will
Path Analysis 169
cover in a subsequent section. Embedded in the diagram are the four
causal assumptionsassociation, temporal ordering, correct effect pri-
ority, and nonspuriousnessthat we hypothesize about the cause and
effect relationships between the variables.
Path diagrams are made up of four geometric symbolssquares or
rectangles, lines with single-headed arrows, lines with double-headed
arrows, and circles. The squares or rectangles are used to represent the
measured variables, be they exogenous or endogenous. Figure 7.1 includes
ve rectangles representing ve measured variablesT1 Caregiver
School Involvement, T1 8th Grade Achievement, T2 Student Motivation,
T2 Extracurricular Involvement, and T3 12th Grade Achievement.
The lines indicate relationships between variables. These lines repre-
sent the required condition of association in establishing causality. Lines
with single-headed arrows ( ) are used to represent the hypothesized
impact of one variable (the cause) on another variable (the effect). These
lines are the paths or relationships that will be tested in the analysis.
Figure 7.1 includes seven single-headed arrow lines or paths connect-
ing hypothesized causes (e.g., T2 Student Motivation) to their respective
effects (e.g., T3 12th Grade Achievement).
Note that the single-headed arrow lines in Figure 7.1 have plus (+)
or minus ( ) signs above them. These signs depict the hypothesized
direction of the causal relationship between the two variables. Thus, a
path diagram shows that two variables are hypothesized to be associ-
ated with one another and what is expected in terms of the nature of
their association. A plus sign indicates a positive association, such that
the stronger the cause, the stronger the effect. A negative sign indicates
an inverse association, such that the stronger the cause, the weaker the
effect.
Lines with double-headed arrows ( ) are used to represent cova-
riances or correlations between two variables. These relationships are
assumed to already exist and are not tested in the analysis. Figure 7.1
has one double-headed arrow line, depicting the correlation between
T1 Caregiver School Involvement and T1 8th Grade Achievement. Thus,
Stewart (2006) posits that T1 Caregiver School Involvement and T1 8th
Grade Achievement are correlated with one another.
The circles represent residual variables . Every endogenous variable
has a residual variable connected to it. Recall that residual variables rep-
resent all of the other causes of the endogenous variable, beyond what
170 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
is included in the model. As shown in Figure 7.1, a residual variable is
connected to each endogenous variable. R 1 represents all causes of 12th
grade achievement, beyond T1 Caregiver School Involvement, T1 8th
Grade Achievement, T2 Student Motivation, and T2 Extracurricular
Involvement. R 2 represents all causes of T2 Extracurricular Involvement,
beyond T1 Caregiver School Involvement and T1 8th Grade Achievement.
Finally, R 3 represents all causes of T2 Student Motivation, beyond T1
Caregiver School Involvement.
Temporal ordering another condition in establishing causalityis
also depicted in a path diagram. By convention, temporal order is orga-
nized from left to right. This means that variables on the left side of a dia-
gram are hypothesized to occur prior in time to variables that are toward
the right side of the diagram. The Figure 7.1 diagram is based on three
points in timeT1, T2, and T3. Two variables are measured at time 1
(i.e., T1 Caregiver School Involvement and T1 8th Grade Achievement).
Two variables are measured at time 2 (i.e., T2 Student Motivation and T2
Extracurricular Involvement). The nal outcome variable (i.e., T3 12th
Grade Achievement) is measured at time 3.
Finally, the path diagram also shows the presumed effect prior-
ity, which is the direction of the causal in uence from one variable to
another. In our example, the direction of in uence is straightforward due
to the time dimension. The diagram re ects Stewarts beliefs that factors
that occur in the eighth grade predict factors that occur subsequently, in
the 10th and 12th grades, and factors that occur during the 10th grade
predict something that occurs in the 12th grade.
Bohrnstedt and Knoke (1994, p. 411) present six rules that guide the
construction of path diagrams, as follows:
1. Variable names are represented by either short key words or
letters.
2. Variables placed to the left in a diagram are assumed to be
causally prior to those on the right.
3. Causal relationships between variables are represented by
single-headed arrows.
4. Variables assumed to be correlated but not causally related are
linked by a curved, double-headed arrow.
5. Variables assumed to be correlated but not causally related should
be at the same point on the horizontal axis of the causal diagram.
Path Analysis 171
6. The causal effect presumed between two variables is indicated
by placing + or signs along the causal arrows to show how
increases or decreases in one variable affect the other.
Types of Relationships between Variables
Figure 7.2 shows diagrams of three types of cause and effect relation-
shipsdirect, mediating, and moderating, adapted from the diagram
provided by Bohrnstedt and Knoke (1994, p. 412). Mediating and mod-
erating cause and effect relationships are also referred to as indirect
effects. Path analysis is used to test two types of causeeffect relation-
shipsdirect and mediating (i.e., intervening). The rst diagram rep-
resents a direct causeeffect relationship between X (the IV) and Y (the
DV). As you can see, Figure 7.1 proposes seven direct causeeffect rela-
tionships (i.e., T1 Caregiver School Involvement T2 Extracurricular
Involvement, T1 Caregiver School Involvement T2 Student Motivation,
T1 Caregiver School Involvement T3 12th Grade Achievement, T1 8th
Grade Achievement T2 Extracurricular Involvement, T1 8th Grade
Achievement 12th Grade Achievement, T2 Student Motivation T3
12th Grade Achievement, and T2 Extracurricular Involvement T3 12th
Grade Achievement).
The second diagram in Figure 7.2 shows a mediating causeeffect
relationship, with the addition of variable Z , occurring in a time-ordered
manner between X and Y . In this case, X affects Y indirectly through Z .
In other words, Z mediates the relationship between X and Y . The vari-
able Z is also referred to as an intervening variable. Figure 7.1 provides
two examples of mediating causeeffect relationships. First, T1 Caregiver
School Involvement is hypothesized to affect T3 12th Grade Achievement
indirectly through T2 Extracurricular Involvement. In other words,

We can distinguish between these mediating effects (commonly
tested in path analysis), and moderating effects based on the interactions
in two-way ANOVA models. Recall that in two-way ANOVA we are inter-
ested in determining whether one IV affects the relationship between
another IV and the DV. In other words, we examine whether the impact
of an IV on the DV is conditioned by another IV. This is displayed in
the fourth diagram in Figure 7.2. Recall the Family Connections evalua-
tion (Lindsey et al., 2010), described in Chapter 6. If the researchers were
interested in examining whether study conditions and family structure
interacted with one another to affect the outcome, they could test the
interaction effect of the study condition and family structure on group
means. This is referred to as a moderating effect because one IV (in this
case, family structure) is hypothesized to alter the strength of the rela-
tionship between another IV (e.g., participation in Family Connections)
and the DV (e.g., improved family functioning).
For further information on mediating and moderating variables, a
widely cited source is Baron and Kinney (1986).
Path Coef cients
A path coef cient is an estimate of the direct, causal relationship between
a causal variable (the IV) and an effect variable (the endogenous or out-
come variable), controlling for other IVs in the sequence. Each line with
a single-headed arrow in the path model has an associated estimated path
Path Analysis 173
coef cient. Thus, the path-analytic method produces as many estimated
path coef cients as there are lines with single-headed arrows. A path
coef cient is represented by the symbol, , with two subscripts. The rst
subscript indicates the effect; the second subscript indicates the cause.
For example, the notation for the estimated path coef cient re ecting
the causal relationship between T1 Caregiver School Involvement T2
Extracurricular Involvement is
EICI

EI
represents the effect variable, T2 Extracurricular Involvement; and
CI
represents the causal variable, T1 Caregiver School Involvement.
Recall our discussion of estimated regression coef cients in Chapter
5. Estimated path coef cients are simply regression coef cients that are
standardized. Standardizing the estimates provides a common unit by
which we can compare the impact of the estimates on the outcomes.
Similar to the unstandardized estimates, standardized estimates are also
considered effect size measures, and CIs can be calculated to determine
their precision relative to the population value. The common unit also
allows us to decompose (i.e., separate) correlations among variables.
We will go over path decomposition in more detail in a subsequent sec-
tion. As with estimated regression coef cients, path coef cients indicate
the direction and relative magnitude of the effects of causal IVs on out-
come variables, controlling for other variables in the sequence. They are
interpreted similarly to estimated regression coef cients. That is, a path
coef cient indicates the amount of expected change in the outcome or
endogenous variable as a result of a one unit change in the causal vari-
able, controlling for other variables in the sequence.
Path coef cients are estimated by regressing each endogenous vari-
able on the IV in the equation. For example, to estimate

Path Decompositions
One of the strengths of path analysis is that it allows us to separate out
the components of the path coef cient (i.e., correlation between two
variables), also called path decomposition. By decomposing these path
correlations, we gain a more complete understanding of the causal rela-
tionships. As indicated previously, we decompose only those path corre-
lations that represent both direct and indirect (i.e., mediated) effects, as
is shown in the path to X
4
in Figure 7.3.
As explained by Olobatuyi (2006), there are up to four components
that make up a path correlation, depending on the type of relationship
between the two variables it representsdirect effect, indirect effect,
unanalyzed correlation, and/or effects from factors not in the model,
also referred to as spurious effects. Particular correlations are made up
of a mix of these components, depending on the hypothesized relation-
ships. For instance, unanalyzed correlations are only associated with
correlated exogenous variables (e.g., the correlation between X
1
and X
2
[r
12
] in Figure 7.3). Furthermore, effects from factors not in the model
(spurious effects [e.g., e 3 and e 4 in Figure 7.3]) are only associated with
endogenous variables (e.g., X
3
and X
4
in Figure 7.3). Finally, some vari-
ables may only be indirectly related to other variables, with no direct
effects.

direct and indirect effects. However, to get a broad understanding of
path decomposition, Table 7.1 (Olobatuyi, 2006, p. 111) provides the
components of all path correlations in Figure 7.3. The rst column
lists the notation for the total association of each path in the model,
represented as r . Note here that the subscript notations differ from the
path-coef cient notations. That is, subscripts for r occur in chrono-
logical order. The second column lists the component representative
176 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
of each paths direct effects. The third column lists the components
that represent the indirect effects of the respective total correlation.
The fourth column lists the components that represent unanalyzed
correlation, and the nal column indicates the components represent-

determine the components of each path coef cient. For example, the

Path Analysis Assumptions and Requirements
Due to their similarity, path analysis and linear regression analysis share
many of the same assumptions. This section provides a brief description
of these assumptions and other model requirements for path analysis.
For more details, refer to Chapter 5.
Assumptions about Variables
The distribution of all variables approximates the shape of a
normal curve.
Variables are measured at the interval or ratio-level.
Exogenous variables are measured without error.
Exogenous variables are not correlated with variables not in the
model.
None of the causal variables are perfectly correlated with one
another (i.e., no multicollinearity).

Assumptions about Relationships
The relationship between the cause and effect variables is linear.
The relationship between the cause and effect variables is
additive. This means that there are no moderating (i.e.,
interaction) effects.
Causation occurs in one direction. In other words, X is assumed
to cause Y , rather than vise versa, and X and Y are not reciprocally
related to one another.
The path model has been accurately speci ed. That is, relevant
variables have been included in the model and the causal
ordering of variables is correct.
Assumptions about Residuals
The mean value of the residuals for all values of X
i
is zero.
The variance of the residuals is constant for all values of X (i.e.,
homogeneity of variance).
The distribution of the residuals should approximate the shape of
a normal curve.
The residuals of exogenous variables are independent of or
uncorrelated with one another (i.e., lack autocorrelation).
The residuals of each endogenous variable are not correlated with
all other causes of that variable.
Other Model Requirements
The minimum recommended sample size is 10 cases to every
parameter in the model (Kline, 1998).
The path model is identi ed . This means that a unique estimate
can be determined for each parameter in the model. Model
identi cation is discussed in the next section.
Model Identi cation
One of the requirements of path analysis is that there must be as many
observations as there are parameters, such that the model is just iden-
ti ed. Before we discuss what this means in terms of path analysis, it
is useful to de ne observations and parameters in the context of path
analysis and identi ed models. In this case, observations are not the
number of cases in the study. Rather, they are the number of variances
178 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
and unique co-variances among the observed variables. We can under-
stand what is meant by unique co-variances by considering a variance
co-variance matrix. In a varianceco-variance matrix, the variances are
provided along the diagonal. The co-variances between pairs of variables
are provided twice in the matrixboth above and below the diagonal. In
path models we include only one set of these co-variances.
The formula for determining the number of observations is: v ( v + 1)
2, where v is the number of observed variables in the model. For example,
the path diagramed in Figure 7.3 includes four observed variables ( X
1
, X
2
,
X
3
, and X
4
). To determine the number of observations in this model we
replace v with 4 and solve the equation. Thus, the number of observa-
tions in this model is 4(4 + 1) 2 = 10.
Model parameters are the estimates that are produced in the analysis.
Parameters include all estimated path coef cients, the correlations among
the exogenous variables, and the variances and co-variances of the exog-
enous variables, including the residuals. For example, in Figure 7.3 we
estimate 10 parameters, including ve path coef cients (i.e.,
