number of observations and the number of parameters are equal.
Because path models are always recursive (i.e., the relationship
between X and Y is unidirectional [ XY ]) and the disturbances (residu-
als) are assumed to be independent (i.e., uncorrelated), it is impossible to
specify a path model that is under identi ed (i.e., more parameters than
observations) or over identi ed (i.e., more observations than parame-
ters). Thus, if your path model is correctly speci ed, it is not necessary to
be concerned about model identi cation in path analysis.
Estimating Path Models
Overview
Path models can be estimated using either standard regression-analysis
methods or with a model tting program, such as AMOS (SPSS Inc.,
2011) or Mplus (Mplus). In multiple regression methods, one must
conduct a separate analysis for each endogenous variable. Model- tting
programs estimate model parameters simultaneously. They also provide
statistics that can be used to evaluate model t; this information is not
Path Analysis 179
provided in multiple regression analysis procedures. We describe how to
estimate path models using a model- tting program (i.e., AMOS) rather
than multiple regression analysis.
Three sets of parameters are estimated in path models1) estimated
path coef cients, representing direct and indirect effects, 2) correlations
between exogenous variables, and 3) the variances and covariances of
the disturbance terms. Their interpretations are straightforward. The
interpretation of estimated path coef cients is similar to the way we
interpret estimated standardized coef cients in linear regression analy-
sis. The correlation between pairs of exogenous variables (i.e., Pearson
r ) is interpreted as the degree of association between them. Finally, esti-
mates of disturbance term variances for endogenous variables indicate
the portion of variation that is not explained by the variables in the
model.
Maximum Likelihood Estimation
Model- tting programs use maximum-likelihood (ML) estimation
rather than the least squares method used in linear regression analy-
sis. The ML estimation process is based on the assumption that the
estimated parameters represent population values. Thus, the intent of
ML estimation is to maximize the likelihood that the obtained sample
estimates re ect the population parameters as closely as possible. In
ML estimation, the parameter estimates are calculated simultaneously
through an iterative process. What happens here is that the statistical
program comes up with an initial set of estimates and then runs through
multiple sets of calculations, seeking to determine the best tting set
of estimates. This iterative process continues until it converges (or not)
on a solution. If iterative estimation is unsuccessful and fails to con-
verge, this will be indicated as part of the output. In previous chapters,
we identi ed several assumptions that are necessary in order to make
inferences about our ndings. The same assumptions are required in
ML estimation.
Evaluating Model Fit
In path analysis with ML estimation, various tests are available to evalu-
ate the t of the model to the data. These tests vary with regard to which
aspect of t is being evaluated. Thus, it is common to use several statisti-
cal t indices to evaluate model t. We review two types of t indices used
180 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
to assess model t in path analysisabsolute t indices and incremental
t indices. For more information on t indices, see Kline (2011).
Absolute t indices . Absolute t indices are used to compare the
observed variances and covariances to the expected variances and covari-
ances, or what Kenny (2011) refers to as the perfect model. The larger
the value of the statistical index, the further the observed model is from
the perfect or expected t. Thus, we seek absolute t indices with rela-
tively small values. Common absolute t indices are the Chi Square test,
the Goodness of Fit Index (GFI), the Standardized Root Mean Square
Residual (SRMR), and the Root Mean Square Error of Approximation
(RMSEA).
Comparative t indices . Comparative t indicesalso referred to as
incremental t indicesare used to assess the improvement in t of the
observed model relative to the baseline or null model. Fit values range
from 0 to 1.0. Larger values indicate better t. In fact, values that are
less than .90 are considered unacceptable. Common incremental t indi-
ces are the Comparative Fit Index (CFI) (Bentler, 1990), the Normed Fit
Index (NFI) (Bentler & Bonett, 1980), and the Non-Normed Fit Index
(NNFI) (Bentler & Bonett).
Path Analysis in Social Work Research: Examples from the Literature
Path analysis has been used to inform important issues to social work
researchers. For instance, Azuma and Chasnoff (1993) used path analy-
sis techniques to examine the impact of in utero drug exposure on sub-
sequent developmental outcomes for toddlers. The researchers used a
prospective, longitudinal design to determine the direct effects of drug
exposure (i.e., exogenous variable) on IQ (the outcome endogenous vari-
able) and whether the effects of drug exposure on IQ were mediated by
three other endogenous variableshead circumference, the home envi-
ronment, and problematic behaviors (i.e., indirect effects). The research-
ers found that prenatal drug exposure had a direct effect on lower IQ
scores for toddlers at age 3. Indirect effects were also reported through all
three of the endogenous variables.
In another example, Ellickson and Hayes (1991) employed path ana-
lytic techniques to examine the direct effects of several cognitive (e.g.,
alcohol expectancies), social (e.g., peer alcohol use), and behavioral
(e.g., academic performance) factors on the frequency of heavy alcohol
Path Analysis 181
use among seventh graders at two subsequent time points3 and 12
months. The researchers also examined whether the frequency of heavy
alcohol use at 3 months mediated relations between the exogenous vari-
ables (i.e., cognitive, social, and behavioral factors) and the frequency of
heavy alcohol use at 12 months. Several variables (e.g., alcohol expectan-
cies) had direct effects on heavy drinking at 12 months. Many of these
relationships (e.g., peer alcohol use) were also mediated by heavy alcohol
use at 3 months.
Finally, Kogan and others (2005) examined whether high school drop-
out status mediated the relationship between prior drug use and problem
behavior on subsequent drug use among 1,762 African American youth.
The data came from the 1990 and 1992 follow-ups of the NELS: 88.
Path modeling indicated that marijuana use, cigarette use, and problem
behavior at time 1 had direct effects on high school dropout at time 2 and
subsequent marijuana and cigarette use at time 3. Results also showed
that dropout status mediated the impact of the time 1 measures on drug
use at time 3.
STRUCTURAL EQUATION MODELS WITH LATENT VARIABLES: AN INTRODUCTION
In the previous section we described path analysis models, which belong
to the structural equation modeling (SEM) family. In this section we
build on the path analysis presentation to present an overview of struc-
tural equation modeling with latent variables. Recall that, in path analy-
sis, we assume that residuals are not correlated with one another and
that causation occurs in a unidirectional fashion (i.e., one way from left
to right), as re ected in a recursive model. SEM permits correlated error
among residuals as well as reciprocal relationships between variables
(i.e., nonrecursive models). In SEM, endogenous variables are referred
to as latent variables . A latent variable cannot be directly observed, and,
as a consequence, is measured indirectly through observed variables or
indicators. By the way, the conventional symbol for a latent variable is a
circle.
Examples of latent variables are attitudes toward homosexuality, per-
ceptions of safety, and extroversion (vs. introversion). One well-known
latent variable is self-esteem, measured using the Rosenberg Self-Esteem
Scale (Rosenberg, 1965). The Rosenberg Self-Esteem Scale is made up of
182 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
10 items that describe aspects of self-esteem. Respondents are asked to
select one of four choices (i.e., strongly agree, agree, disagree, or strongly
disagree) that most closely indicates their views of each item. Responses
to all items are then combined to determine a measure of self-esteem for
each respondent.
SEM with latent variables involves a combination of factor-analytic
and path analytic techniques, representing two models. One model is
called the measurement model and is tested using factor analysis. The
other model is called the structural model and is estimated using path
analysis techniques. Lets focus rst on the measurement model. The
purpose of the measurement model is to con rm that hypothesized
indicators (i.e., observed variables) represent latent variables (i.e., unob-
served variables), albeit imperfectly. Through this process we attempt to
operationalize concepts, such as self-esteem, that are dif cult to measure
because they are not easily observable. Applying the self-esteem exam-
ple to an SEM framework, we would test the measurement model using
factor-analytic techniques to determine the extent to which responses to
the 10-item Rosenberg Self-Esteem Scale actually measure the latent or
unobserved variableself-esteem.
Once we have established relationships between observed and unob-
served or latent variables, we then test the second component of SEM, the
structural model. This is simply a test of the factors derived in the mea-
surement model using the path analytic techniques we discussed previ-
ously. However, in this case, the endogenous variables are often latent
or unobserved, and causal relationships may be reciprocal rather than
just unidirectional. For those of you who are interested in learning more
about structural equation modeling, we recommend Bowen and Guo
(2012).
CONDUCTING PATH ANALYSIS IN AMOS: EXAMPLE
To summarize, path analysis is used to determine causal relationships
between exogenous and endogenous variables. Endogenous variables
must be measured on an interval or ratio-level. The following provides
instructions for conducting path analysis in AMOS, using data from
NELS: 88. A more detailed set of instructions is available on the compan-
ion website of this book.
Path Analysis 183
Socioeconomic status (BYSES), self-concept (BYCNCPT1), and time
spent on English homework each week (BYS79C) at time 1 are mod-
eled as exogenous variables predicting time 1 standardized reading scores
(BY2XRSTD); time 1 standardized reading scores (BY2XRSTD) are
modeled as an endogenous variable predicting time 2 standardized read-
ing scores (F12XRSTD). The data come from a random sample of 1,500
cases selected from NELS:88/92 dataset with no missing observations in
any of the variables. The SPSS data set used for this example is PATH
ANALYSIS.sav. IBM AMOS version 19 is used for this demonstration.
Click IBM AMOS 19 and click Amos Graphics to open AMOS.
To import the SPSS data le into AMOS, click File.
A drop down menu will appear. Move your cursor to Data Files
and click to open the Data Files dialog box.
Click File Name. Locate the SPSS data le, click on it and click
open. This will bring you back to the Data Files dialog box. The
data le is under File. Click OK.
Specify the model by drawing a diagram that includes all of
the variables. The exogenous and endogenous variables are
represented as rectangles. To draw the BYSES rectangle, click
Diagram and then click Draw Observed.
Move the mouse to the location for the BYSES rectangle in the
drawing area. Press the left mouse button to draw the rectangle.
Release the mouse button to complete the rectangle. Follow the
same steps to draw the rectangles of the other four variables.
Once the rectangles have been drawn, click the rectangle icon to
deactivate it.
Draw ovals to represent the residual variables for the endogenous
variables. Click Diagram and then click Draw Unobserved.
Move the mouse to the location for the rst residual variable in
the drawing area. Press the left mouse button to draw the rst
oval. Release the mouse button. Follow the same steps to draw the
oval of the other endogenous variable.
Once the ovals have been drawn, click the oval icon to deactivate it.
D e ne the variables. Double click on the rst rectangle that
represents BYSES (socioeconomic status). The Object Properties
dialog box appears. Click the Text tab and type BYSES in the
Variable name eld. Close the Object Property box by clicking
184 Basic Statistics in Multivariate Analysis
X at the top right corner. Repeat this with the other rectangles
and ovals. Remember that the names given to the observed
variables must match the variable names in the SPSS data le.
Draw paths connecting the observed variables using single-headed
arrows. To draw a single-headed arrow, click on the single-headed
arrow (i.e., Draw Paths) icon from the toolbar (just below the
rectangle icon). Click and hold down the left mouse button from
the right edge of BYSES to the left edge of BY2XRSTD rectangle.
Clicking the BYSES rectangle will illuminate the edges of the
rectangle in red. Release the mouse button when the BY2XRSTD
rectangle edge is illuminated in green. Repeat this procedure for
the remaining paths with single-headed arrows.
W h e n nished drawing the single headed arrow paths, click the
single-headed arrow icon to deactivate it.
Draw paths between the exogenous variables using
double-headed arrows. To draw a double-headed arrow path,
click on the double-headed arrow (i.e., Draw Covariances)
icon. Click and hold down the left mouse button from the left
edge of the BYCNCPT1 rectangle to the left edge of the BYSES
rectangle. Repeat this procedure for the remaining paths with
double-headed arrows.
After drawing the double-headed arrow path, click on the
double-headed arrow icon to deactivate it.
D e ne the scale of the residual variables (V) and (B) by xing the
path coef cients from V to F12XRSTD and B to BY2XRSTD to
1. Double click on the path between V and F12XRSTD to open
the Object Properties dialog box. Click on the Parameters tab and
enter 1 in the Regression weight box. Click the X on the upper
right hand corner of the dialog box to close it. Repeat these steps
to de ne the scale of B.
To perform the analyses, click View and then Analysis
Properties. Click the Output tab and check Minimization
history, Standardized estimates, and Squared multiple
correlations. Close the Analysis Properties window by clicking
the X in the top right corner. Click Analyze and then Calculate
Estimates.
The Save As dialog box will appear. Select the location where you
want to save it, name the le, and click Save. The saved le for
Path Analysis 185
this example is available on the companion website. The name of
the le is, Path Analysis Tutorial.
Once the le has been saved, the model estimates are calculated.
To view the text output, click View and then Text Output.
Links to nine components of the output are provided in the left
pane. To view a particular component, click on it. The details
appear in the right pane. To exit the text output window, click on
the X on the upper right hand corner of the dialog box.
To view the graphics output, click the View Output icon next
to the drawing area. The unstandardized estimates appear on
the path diagram. To view the standardized estimates, click
Standardized estimates in the third box below the output icon.
NOTE: A copy of the output is available on the companion
website. The le is named, Path Analysis Output.pdf.

of the means
Standard score the number of standard deviations a raw score falls above or
below the mean; also referred to as a z score
Statistic a numeric value that summarizes a feature of a sample
Statistical multiple regression a method of data entry for conducting multiple
linear regression analysis in which the order that the independent variables are
entered into the equation is determined by statistics rather than by theory; also
referred to as stepwise multiple regression
Stepwise multiple regression a method of data entry for conducting multiple
linear regression analysis in which the order that the independent variables are
entered into the equation is determined by statistics rather than by theory; also
referred to as statistical multiple regression
Structural-equation modeling a family of statistical techniques used to estimate
causal relations among variables
Structural model in structural equation modeling a model that represents
hypothesized causal relationships between variables
200 Glossary
Sum of squared residuals a measure of the leftover sum of squares or the dif-
ference between the predicted data points on the best tting regression line
and the actual observed data points; represents the errors in prediction; also
referred to as residual sum of squares
Suppressor variable a type of moderating variable that affects the relationship
between the independent and dependent variable such that, if the suppressor
variable is not included in the analysis, the relationship between the indepen-
dent and dependent variable is not statistically signi cant; also referred to as a
obscuring variable
Systematic measurement error discrepancies between measured and actual
(true) values of a variable which are more likely to be higher or lower than
the actual values of the variable; also known as bias in measurement.
Temporal ordering (i.e., precedence) in the order that something occurred in
time; the presumed cause preceded the presumed effect; one of the conditions
required for establishing causality between two variables
Total sum of squares a measure of the combined sum of squares predicted by
the regression equation (i.e., model sum of squares) and the leftover or resid-
ual sum of squares
Trimmed mean the mean of a distribution of values calculated after disregard-
ing a percentage of the lowest and highest values; serves to reduce the effects
of outliers in the data
Two-tailed hypothesis a hypothesis that predicts a signi cant relationship
between variables, but does not predict the direction of the relationship; also
referred to as a nondirectional hypothesis
Two-way analysis of variance a type of ANOVA used to examine models with
one dependent variable, measured at the interval or ratio level and two inde-
pendent variables measured at the nominal levels
Type I error the chance of concluding that the relationship between variables is
a real one (rejecting the null hypothesis) when, in fact, there is not a real rela-
tionship between variables in the population (equal to the p value)
Type II error the chance of concluding that there is no relationship between
variables (failing to reject the null hypothesis) when, in fact, there is a real
relationship between variables in the population
Univariate statistical methods statistical methods that organize and summarize
data one variable at a time
Validity the accuracy of a method of measurement
Variable a concept or characteristic in a research study that varies
Variance the average squared distance between the mean and each value in a
distribution of values
Weights values assigned to the coef cients of the equations that represent the
contrasts
Glossary 201
Within-groups variability (i.e., variance) in ANOVA, one of two types of vari-
ability; differences of the mean scores across participants in the same group,
relative to the overall mean for that group
Within-groups sum of squares one of two components of total sums of squares
in ANOVA; represents the variability or variation in scores within each group
z score the number of standard deviations a raw score falls above or below the
mean; also referred to as a standard score
